If both source and destination volumes are on NFS backend, this patch looks no problem.

But if the destination volume is created on the thick LVM, we might copy full block without conv=sparse because the thick LVM volume might not be zero cleared.

In my understanding, we should check functionality of volume zero cleared for destination host at first, and then we decide whether we can use conv=sparse parameter or not.
We can use this parameter only if the destination volume is ensured zero cleared beforehand to avoid security issue.

I proposed this approach at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/183701/

Any thought?'}, {'account_id': 13900, 'date': '2015-05-20 03:11:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add ability for drivers to copy data preserving sparseness

Drivers can set self._sparse_copy_volume_data to opt in
to copying data in a way that preserves sparseness.

This is likely to be desired elsewhere, but currently this
patch only enables it for the NFS driver and provides a
method for other drivers to opt in, in case there are
unexpected issues in some drivers.

On the NFS driver, this prevents volume migration from
changing a volume file from sparse to fully allocated.

Change-Id: Ib74b2fb4015b805d33de42dfe60c8a97cc970b84
Closes-Bug: #1455595

commit_message:
Disable oslo.vmware test dependency on Python 3

oslo.vmware 0.12.0 still requires suds which is not compatible with
Python 3. Next oslo.vmware will uses suds-jurko. Disable the dependency
until the next oslo.vmware release.

oslo.vmware change using suds-jurko:
I699c65e4abd607ea6f377d86c45fd609569f3c2b

Blueprint nova-python3
Change-Id: Ia05c433736128f0d1a64c73b556f6283894c49c7

subject: Run tests with PyMySQL on Python 3

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-13 15:07:00.000000000', 'message': "Replace MySQL-python with PyMySQL in tests

MySQL-python doesn't work on Python 3. Replace it with PyMySQL to be
able to run Nova tests on Python 3.

This change doesn't force deployers to use PyMySQL, it only impacts Nova
tests.

Blueprint nova-python3
Change-Id: I5a27c7d627105b614da3cab3a87296a8e186b555
"}, {'created': '2015-05-13 16:19:58.000000000', 'message': 'Run tests with PyMySQL on Python 3

Add test-requirements-py3.txt to use PyMySQL, instead of MySQL-python,
on Python 3.

Add a py34 test environment to tox.ini which uses
test-requirements-py3.txt and sets OS_TEST_DBAPI_ADMIN_CONNECTION to use
the PyMySQL connector instead of the MySQL-python connector.

This change is based on Ironic tox.ini, so I added Victor Sergeyev as
the coauthor of the patch.

Co-Authored-By: Victor Sergeyev <vsergeyev@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Run tests with PyMySQL on Python 3

Add test-requirements-py3.txt to use PyMySQL, instead of MySQL-python,
on Python 3.

Add a py34 test environment to tox.ini which uses
test-requirements-py3.txt and sets OS_TEST_DBAPI_ADMIN_CONNECTION to use
the PyMySQL connector instead of the MySQL-python connector.

This change is based on Ironic tox.ini, so I added Victor Sergeyev as
the coauthor of the patch.

Co-Authored-By: Victor Sergeyev <vsergeyev@mirantis.com>
Blueprint nova-python3
Change-Id: I5a27c7d627105b614da3cab3a87296a8e186b555

commit_message:
Correct host aggregate and availability zone info

The documentation around the creation of host aggregates and
availability zones. In particular indicating that a host could be in
multiple availability zones.

Change-Id: I56ea99cfe004b58ed903702b20896c479fa43644
Closes-Bug: #1433673

commit_message:
Fix functional tests in gate

The check-glanceclient-dsvm-functional gate job was failing due to the
functional tests not picking up valid OpenStack credentials.

Update how we aquire credentials -- fixes side effect of how tox 2.0
handles environment variables.

Change-Id: Ia665dc9673d09421508476d05039d2da8a5e1a29
Closes-bug: 1455102

[{'created': '2015-05-25 16:29:43.000000000', 'message': 'Add Manila project support

Manila provides management of shared or distributed filesystems.

Add support for Manila project main features:
- Create/delete share
- Create/delete share-network
- Create/delete security-service
- Add security service to share network

Change-Id: I6092ce2639745801334c5a5be63062de9e79207c
'}]
commit_message:
Add Manila project support

Manila provides management of shared or distributed filesystems.

Add support for Manila project main features:
- Create/delete share
- Create/delete share-network
- Create/delete security-service
- Add security service to share network

Change-Id: I6092ce2639745801334c5a5be63062de9e79207c

[{'created': '2015-05-21 22:03:55.000000000', 'message': "Add domains negative test

Created domain can't be removed by simple call, it's necessary to
disable it at first and then remove it. Otherwise Forbidden exception
will be raised.

Change-Id: I20a9d58c3bcc07c5483b43f7cba13f82d177c46a
"}]
commit_message:
Add domains negative test

Created domain can't be removed by simple call, it's necessary to
disable it at first and then remove it. Otherwise Forbidden exception
will be raised.

Change-Id: I20a9d58c3bcc07c5483b43f7cba13f82d177c46a

Kyle, this is what it says:

"The monolithic plugins and ML2 MechanismDrivers become integration-only to code that lives outside the tree (more details to follow below); the same applies for any vendor-specific agents. The only part that will remain in the tree is the agent entry points (a small python file that imports agent code from the vendor library and starts it)."

If I understand this correctly it means that the ML2 plugin will still remain in the tree. I have a number of concerns and problems with this:
1. The fact that the ML2 drivers will be pulled out is OK, but the ML2 plugin should also be. The Ml2 plugin should be treated like any other plugin.
2. Making changes to the ML2 plugin will still have the same issues described in the spec.
3. My two cents is that the ML2 plugin is the reference example for the community. So here we should be showing how it can lead the way with the plugin decomposition.
4. Not all of the plugins will be on an equal footing.
5. The fact that one plugin is in tree and others are not will be an accident waiting to happen.
6. What happens tomorrow when we want to make the ODL plugin be the default plugin. Will that be added to the tree and the ML2 plugin blown away from the tree?

I understand that the community wants to split plugin out, but it should be the same policy for all plugins, irrespective if one is used for gating.

Thanks
Gary'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-12-07 07:36:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Hi,
By leaving it in tree due to technical reasons implies that we will encounter technical reasons with the plugins that are to be moved out of the tree. That is where things are really going to hurt.

My thinking is as follows: We do the ML2 as a reference architecture. This can be done in the following steps:
i. Create a new directory with the ML2 plugin shim (that is what is proposed for all plugins)
ii. Create a stackforge repo with ML2 (this may require work for the shims for the vendor drivers - but that can be done in parallel)
iii. Update devstack to work with the aforementioned
Having the following up and running will 'free' developers to work on their various plugins etc. Once we see that the devstack driver with the ML2 shim works then we flip that to be the default one for gating and hit the stopwatch for all the others to get going.

That will enable us as a community to work together on code and get it up and running ASAP.

Leaving the gating reference architecture to be done last is problematic in my opinion. Since day one in Quantum/Neutron the reference has always led the way - showing the community what is expected etc.

Thanks
Gary"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-12-07 20:12:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

@Henry, the fact that certain bits remain in tree and others are removed is a problem due to the fact that we do not have versioned API's.
There are going to be cases when the gate passes with the OVS driver and all others drivers fail due to an API change. This is a example in review at the moment - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125115/.
From an architectural perspective we need to make sure that our model works with all plugins. A change in the base DB plugin class will be fixed immediately in the ML2 plugin as it is in tree and others will have to try and understand what things break. This process will continue until we have versioned API's/interfaces. I do not think that there is a plan on tagging the neutron branch at the moment.

Once again, I stress that I am not opposed to the proposal in general as it may give the community a chance to speed things up. But I really think that we should have all plugins behave in the same manner - that is the only "tool" that we have at the moment to keep sane.

But I guess that the onus is going to be on the vendors, maintainers, trailblazers, and whoever tries their adventure with Neutron.

But I seem to be a minority ...'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2014-12-09 16:38:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

The current proposal is to keep the integration layer of each vendor driver in the same tree as the ML2 plugin, but move as much as possible of the backend-specific logic to external libraries maintained by each vendor. Code that implements or directly uses the ML2 driver APIs should remain in-tree, focusing the review effort on the usage of the driver API and allowing that driver API to continue to evolve without the overhead of supporting multiple versions simultaneously. Of course out-of-tree drivers are always an option as well. 

Personally, I see no unsurmountable issues, and maybe some advantages, to eventually moving the ML2 plugin, along with its (integration layer) drivers, into a separate official project within the networking program, probably with its own core review team. This would leave the core neutron repo with no functioning data plane, so much of the tempest testing would need to move to this new project, which seems unreasonable to accomplish during kilo, especially with all the refactoring going on. But this currently proposed "decomposition" work seems like a good first step for kilo that should help address the core review bottleneck.'}, {'account_id': 13523, 'date': '2014-12-09 19:41:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

I would like to add a few additional points. I think that once there is the decomposition each plugin will go off on there own direction and the community will not share anything, that is each plugin will just care about what they do and make sure that their bits work.

Each plugin will start to implement its own helper methods etc. The fact that this type of thing can be shared will be lost. In my minds eye that is a loss for the community and the project. Each vendor or sub-project will be on their own kick and only make sure that their bits works.

Where will the community value come into play here?
How do we as a community ensure that the code lying in another repo behaves correctly (please see https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/89320a397112761912ba4ceea68542411531b9c5 - this if I recall correctly was that it did not interface with keystone in the expected manner - I may be wrong - Mark McClain may be able to explain better). This is actually a good example when two cores did not see the issue in the review but a third one caught it (I am one of the two ignorant ones).

I am not sure how we are going to address issues like that when all of the code is distributed all over the place.

The upside of the proposal is that a new contributor will be given the freedom to do what they want - as long as their initial shim is approved. The downside is that they will not even work or contribute on the project. Why should they?

With the service plugins being split out how much of a burden do we really have? That should also free up some core cycles.

commit_message:
Proposal for Neutron core and vendor code decomposition

This spec outlines the plan for addressing the pain points
that every Neutron contributor feels on a daily basis when
working with the project.

The proposed change should be implemented collaboratively,
in the same spirit of the OpenStack community.

This is initial attempt at making this project a thriving
one. We should all recognize that if nothing gets done,
Neutron will become a desolated land where just tumbleweeds
will abound.

Blueprint: core-vendor-decomposition

Change-Id: I7156edbeeed8d5e11415d3feb5b340bbe74e327f

So I have some issues with the tests here:

1. I don't see the need for the config option that is being added here, maybe I don't understand the concept of default domains, but from what it looks like here you are not testing here anything that seems to be unique with that concept. Is there a special metadata flag to show that the domain is the default one?  How do you set the default domain? Both of those things would be testing default domains, but if you can set a default domain from the api then I definitely don't think there is a need for a config option then.

2. For the delete negative test it looks to me like you could just create a new domain and then enable it to test the same thing instead of requiring an already active one from a config option. (at least based on your comment) What is unique about that test to default domains?

3. The test to see if the config option is valid is bogus, you're not testing anything in the keystone, just a local config. This would belong outside of a test in setup since it is really a requirement for your second test and not a test in itself.

Also, you also shouldn't remove a pre-existing copyright header. Additionally, you're pointing to a blueprint that doesn't exist in the commit message."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-07-01 19:41:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

mtreinish the default domain is special. If you could delete it would be big issue. Disabling it also has side effect to the parallel v2 tests.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-07-02 04:55:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: No score

@mpavlasek:
The default domain is added when the db created and it's id is 'default', however it is configurable option in keystone, do you really think it really must be configurable? I have doubts is anybody will ever change it."}, {'account_id': 6683, 'date': '2013-07-02 08:39:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Related keystone change is https://blueprints.launchpad.net/keystone/+spec/default-domain.

Generally - default domain is much more important than just as a part of setup. It's required for backward compatibility of keystone v3 to v2. As in v2 there were no domains, whatever you do there actually should be happening in 'the default domain'. And that domain is also special in that instead of generated UUID it has just string 'default' as ID.

Not sure about that we really need it as config option in tempest, but it's based on that it can be also configured in keystone.conf, so if we would be running against instance with different default domain id.

Agree that "default_domain_incorrect_delete" is weird, as it has actually nothing to do with "just default domain" - it applies to all domains.

As concept of default domain is actually about v2 X v3 compatibility, maybe it would be better to do more than/instead of just checking the domain-exists.

commit_message:
Added test of default domain in Keystone

Default domain is part of Keystone APIv3 domains feature added in Grizzly
backward compatibility for APIv2 which is not aware of domain concept.

Summary of scope this change:
* added new variable 'default_domain_id'
  in tempest.conf (default value 'default')
* new test: default domain must exists (backward compatibility)

Change-Id: Ib77d259e2f377ff19e2cf40fa164f42c0669ea56

[{'created': '2015-05-05 17:33:42.000000000', 'message': 'Use single connection in get_all function for getting "enabled" values for all ldap users.

LDAP being enabled, any keystone commands that use get_all takes a lot of time, especially if there are many LDAP users (like ~3000),
due to the fact that _get_enabled makes a new connection for each user.
Instead, I thought it would be better if a connection is made before the for loop in get_all,
get all "enabled" values from all users, and then close the connection.
I actually tested this code change on mine, and it actually speeds up many keystone commands (user-list, user-role-add, user-delete, user-get).
Before it took about 50 seconds, but now, it takes about 4 seconds.

Closes-Bug: #1451910
Change-Id: I3f5131c9eefa066f0d8ee5127322d686e09308df

'}, {'created': '2015-05-05 21:09:46.000000000', 'message': 'Use single connection in get_all function

As the number of LDAP users increase, any keystone commands that
need to look through all of the LDAP users tend to slow down.
After some investigation, I figured out that the cause of this
is making a new connection for each user in get_all.

In get_all, it calls _get_enabled function for each LDAP user.
In _get_enabled function, a new connection from get_connection()
is created, an then "enabled" value for a user is obtained.
Therefore, the more LDAP users you have, the slower the response
will be.

If a connection is made before the for loop in get_all, get all
"enabled" values from all users, and then close the connection,
then the response from keystone commands would be faster.

This code change was tested on a VM, and it actually speeded up
many keystone commands (user-list, user-role-add, user-delete,
user-get) from 50 seconds to 4 seconds.

Closes-Bug: #1451910
Change-Id: I3f5131c9eefa066f0d8ee5127322d686e09308df

commit_message:
Use single connection in get_all function

As the number of LDAP users increase, any keystone commands that
need to look through all of the LDAP users tend to slow down.
After some investigation, I figured out that the cause of this
is making a new connection for each user in get_all.

In get_all, it calls _get_enabled function for each LDAP user.
In _get_enabled function, a new connection from get_connection()
is created, an then "enabled" value for a user is obtained.
Therefore, the more LDAP users you have, the slower the response
will be.

If a connection is made before the for loop in get_all, get all
"enabled" values from all users, and then close the connection,
then the response from keystone commands would be faster.

This code change was tested on a VM, and it actually speeded up
many keystone commands (user-list, user-role-add, user-delete,
user-get) from 50 seconds to 4 seconds.

Closes-Bug: #1451910
Change-Id: I3f5131c9eefa066f0d8ee5127322d686e09308df

commit_message:
Avoid useless copy in get_instance_metadata()

API.get_instance_metadata() of nova.compute.api creates an useless copy
of a dictionary: return directly the original dictionary created by
SQLAlchemy.

Change-Id: Ifd455e70002eb9636b87f83788384127ba6edeeb

commit_message:
httpretty can fail in Python 3.4 with wrong LC_ALL

if LC_ALL is 'C' then installation in a tox environment fails [1].

[1] https://github.com/gabrielfalcao/HTTPretty/issues/223

Change-Id: I340c88ea7d098ca5943d60adc73f63a0af79a405

commit_message:
Support for concurrent full-stack tests

This patch introduces the last step of complete test separation for
full-stack tests - separate rabbitmq queues - in the form of rabbitmq
virtual hosts.

* This patch also renames EnvironmentFixture to FullstackFixture, for
  clarity.

Change-Id: I24776e3970a73fdd3271023da7967f2c7261621b
Closes-bug: #1452737

commit_message:
Don't run kolla functional gate as root

Because of a recent change, docker image building cannot be done
as the root user.  This is a good thing ;)  But breaks the current
gate.

Also we have a setup_docker.sh script already in our tools directory,
so rename the script we are running to setup_gate.sh because that is
actually what the script does.

Change-Id: I8f86616fb19b4b03f34fe40acf1689f6b174ff98

commit_message:
ensure collections created on upgrade

upgrade does not check that collections exists. this can cause
issues when running upgrade before any data is inserted. this patch
creates collection on upgrade of db2nosql as it does for mongodb.

Change-Id: Iea79688ed81866c0b00aaa80f101b6f045af5bc1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-22 15:11:54.000000000', 'message': "Fix rabbit OCF demote/stop/promote actions

* When the rabbit node went down, its status remains 'running'
  in mnesia db for a while, so few retries (50 sec of total) are
  required in order to kick and forget this node from the cluster.
  This also requires +50 sec for actions stop & demote timeout.
* The rabbit master score in the CIB is retained after the current
  master moved manually. This is wrong and the score must be reset
  ASAP for post-demote and post-stop as well.
* The demoted node must be kicked from cluster by other nodes
  on post-demote processing.
* Post-demote should stop the rabbit app at the node being demoted as
  this node should be kicked from the cluster by other nodes.
  But it stops the app at the *other* nodes instead.

Closes-bug: #1436812
Closes-bug: #1455761

Change-Id: Ib01c1731b4f06e6b643a4bca845828f7db507ad3
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
"}, {'created': '2015-05-22 16:34:37.000000000', 'message': 'Fix rabbit OCF demote/stop/promote actions

* When the rabbit node went down, its status remains 'running'
  in mnesia db for a while, so few retries (50 sec of total) are
  required in order to kick and forget this node from the cluster.
  This also requires +50 sec for actions stop & demote timeout.
* The rabbit master score in the CIB is retained after the current
  master moved manually. This is wrong and the score must be reset
  ASAP for post-demote and post-stop as well.
* The demoted node must be kicked from cluster by other nodes
  on post-demote processing.
* Post-demote should stop the rabbit app at the node being demoted as
  this node should be kicked from the cluster by other nodes.
  But it stops the app at the *other* nodes instead.
* The check to join should be only done at the post-start and not at
  the post-promote, otherwise promoting node thinks it is clustered
  with another node vs the check reported as "already clustered".
  (the regression was caused by https://review.openstack.org/184671)

Closes-bug: #1436812
Closes-bug: #1455761

Change-Id: Ib01c1731b4f06e6b643a4bca845828f7db507ad3
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
'}, {'created': '2015-05-23 01:44:19.000000000', 'message': "Fix rabbit OCF demote/stop/promote actions

* When the rabbit node went down, its status remains 'running'
  in mnesia db for a while, so few retries (50 sec of total) are
  required in order to kick and forget this node from the cluster.
  This also requires +50 sec for actions stop & demote timeout.
* The rabbit master score in the CIB is retained after the current
  master moved manually. This is wrong and the score must be reset
  ASAP for post-demote and post-stop as well.
* The demoted node must be kicked from cluster by other nodes
  on post-demote processing.
* Post-demote should stop the rabbit app at the node being demoted as
  this node should be kicked from the cluster by other nodes.
  But it stops the app at the *other* nodes instead.
* The check to join for post-promote action should be done only
  for the slaves, while the master should not do anything on
  post-promote
  (the regression was caused by https://review.openstack.org/184671)
* Change `hostname` call to `crm_node -n` everywhere to ensure
  we are using correct pacemaker node name
* Introduce functions to get pacemaker node names:
  a) to get all alive nodes in the partition
  b) to get all nodes
  This fixes get_monitor behaviour so that it ignores
  attributes for dead nodes as crm_node behaviour
  changed with upgrade of pacemaker

Closes-bug: #1436812
Closes-bug: #1455761

commit_message:
Fix rabbit OCF demote/stop/promote actions

* When the rabbit node went down, its status remains 'running'
  in mnesia db for a while, so few retries (50 sec of total) are
  required in order to kick and forget this node from the cluster.
  This also requires +50 sec for actions stop & demote timeout.
* The rabbit master score in the CIB is retained after the current
  master moved manually. This is wrong and the score must be reset
  ASAP for post-demote and post-stop as well.
* The demoted node must be kicked from cluster by other nodes
  on post-demote processing.
* Post-demote should stop the rabbit app at the node being demoted as
  this node should be kicked from the cluster by other nodes.
  Instead, it stops the app at the *other* nodes and brings full
  cluster downtime.
* The check to join should be only done at the post-start and not at
  the post-promote, otherwise the node being promoted may think it
  is clustered with some node while the join check reports it as
  already clustered with another one.
  (the regression was caused by https://review.openstack.org/184671)
* Change `hostname` call to `crm_node -n` via $THIS_PCMK_NODE
  everywhere to ensure we are using correct pacemaker node name
* Handle empty values for OCF_RESKEY_CRM_meta_notify_* by reporting
  the resource as not running. This will rerun resource and restore
  its state, eventually.

Closes-bug: #1436812
Closes-bug: #1455761

Change-Id: Ib01c1731b4f06e6b643a4bca845828f7db507ad3
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Remove the custom duplicate check on cluster template update

There is no need for a custom check here, we can let sqlalchemy
enforce the uniqueness constraints. Changed the exception message
to conform to other duplication checks.

Change-Id: Ia80be1d1a40910c9cc30c2fa8d4253c370fdb2df

commit_message:
Refactor internal API of update subnet routes

Refactor internal API of update subnet routes.
1 Prepare code to easy add vpn routes processing
2 Prevent updating routes for explicitly associated subnets in case of
default VPC route table reassociation.
3 Make sequence of API parameters more natural.

Change-Id: Ifcb9b4541156449da1ff74d171a3ac35266577b9

Does it fix the problem? Because I don't really see how it does. According to logs in bug description, error occurred in periodic_task file of openstack.common code. oslo_log doesn't imported here. Besides this, oslo_log uses context from oslo_context and changes in sahara context will have no effect."}, {'account_id': 6116, 'date': '2015-05-20 01:09:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Andrey Pavlov	

Yes, this time I have carefully tested, and the issue is gone for sure.

The reason for the error happen is because, when we do log under a context, the log format would be followed by logging_context_format_string in sahara.conf. 

When devstack install sahara, “logging_context_format_string” has be configured by default to:

logging_context_format_string = %(asctime)s.%(msecs)03d %(color)s%(levelname)s %(name)s [^[[01;36m%(request_id)s ^[[00;36m%(user_name)s %(project_name)s%(color)s] ^[[01;35m%(instance)s%(color)s%(message)s^[[00m

But we don’t have user_name & project_name, we’re using username: https://github.com/openstack/sahara/blob/master/sahara/context.py#L40

The error do not happen until we merged https://review.openstack.org/#/c/172426/12/sahara/service/periodic.py.
When we do LOG.debug with a Context instance.

I first summit a patch to devstack https://review.openstack.org/#/c/180051/, and they suggest to do it in sahara, and that's why I wrongly tested last time. I have devstack changed already."}, {'account_id': 12039, 'date': '2015-05-20 13:26:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Fix logging_context_format_string input for sahara

1. Revert change I960d1fddee8c99c65f13841b37675512dd1ecfd2
   The change do not close bug #1451631 because oslo_log
   get context by context.to_dict().
   https://github.com/openstack/oslo.log/blob/master/oslo_log/formatters.py#L31

2. add "user_name" & "project_name" in context.to_dict().
Closes-Bug: #1451631

Change-Id: I39e54e7a45416c8167485a0d7ebb8afe180560bf

commit_message:
Change RadosGW port to 35357 in granular deployment

Commit I1ef8030b39256a17ef3b1dc1e1061c756d7392a6 changed the default port only
in ceph module. It gets overwritten in ceph-radosgw task used in
granular deployment.

Change-Id: I2ac378bd8fd5a960d7983904b3395c00d5827d60
Closes-Bug: 1446704

commit_message:
Support PUT in Image v2 API

Not only is there a difference between put and task uploads, there is
also a difference between v1 put and v2 put. Of course there is.

Co-Authored-By: David Shrewsbury <shrewsbury.dave@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I63f8dd4279cf242da7e76018580479968bc9aaef

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-19 21:19:57.000000000', 'message': "[HDP] java64_home not pointing at default-installed JDK for plugin

At this time HDP's java64_home property defaults to /opt/jdk1.6.0_31.
However, the now-default openjdk element installs to /usr/lib/jvm/java-openjdk.
If nodes are connected to the internet at cluster spinup time, this does not
cause an overt error, but querying for JDK location will return error code 2,
resulting in no -j argument being passed to 'ambari-server setup -s', which in
turn will result in a download of Oracle's JDK and successful installation. In
the case that the nodes cannot connect to the internet (which should be a
success case with a pre-installed VM image,) cluster creation fails at this
stage.

This patch updates java64_home to the default JAVA_HOME from the openjdk
element.

Change-Id: I1d53db67341626190e7240f0ae4165f91d364a2c
Closes-bug: 1453165
"}]
commit_message:
[HDP] java64_home not pointing at default-installed JDK for plugin

At this time HDP's java64_home property defaults to /opt/jdk1.6.0_31.
However, the now-default openjdk element installs to /usr/lib/jvm/java-openjdk.
If nodes are connected to the internet at cluster spinup time, this does not
cause an overt error, but querying for JDK location will return error code 2,
resulting in no -j argument being passed to 'ambari-server setup -s', which in
turn will result in a download of Oracle's JDK and successful installation. In
the case that the nodes cannot connect to the internet (which should be a
success case with a pre-installed VM image,) cluster creation fails at this
stage.

This patch updates java64_home to the default JAVA_HOME from the openjdk
element.

Change-Id: I1d53db67341626190e7240f0ae4165f91d364a2c
Closes-bug: 1453165

commit_message:
Bring back landing page contents

A brand new file replaced index.rst (now it
is index_content.rst) to provide
HTML layout for the page.
This commit restores the change
for index_content.rst.

Change-Id: Ic14e86632cb4182468e9493bef8dbde536f896ea

commit_message:
Fix playbooks for OpenStack CI

The OpenStack CI systems are preconfigured with various components
such as databases, message queues, caching dns resolvers.  The
CI systems also lack things like public/private key pairs, and
known_hosts files.

Due to this, a number of minor changes are required in Bifrost's test
sequence to account for and route around these differences in order
to allow test jobs to run until completion. This also demonstrated
that some steps have been operating under the assumption that the user
likely already had certain things installed, so service restart
tweeks have also been necessary.

Added a step to restart libvirt-bin in order to allow it to pickup
new capabilities due to the install of the qemu emulator.

Added additional steps to collect kernel log and `virsh capabilities`
output.

Removed MySQL step nolog statements as the password is automatically
suppressed and it suppresses information that could be required for
troubleshooting.

Added in specific username/password logic for MySQL steps if ZUUL
is detected in order to use the OpenStack CI defaults.

Changed VM test node creation to occur upon every attempt.

Extended the startup wait for a test node to be 900 seconds from 600
seconds.

Added collection of process list and listening sockets if ZUUL is
detected.

Added report of VM console log and various commands to assist in
troubleshooting a failing job.

Added auto-generation of a user ssh keypair if absent when operating
in OpenStack CI.

Added explicit adjustment of iptables to permit connections on the
network interface that the hosts are being provisioned via on
8080/tcp and 6385/tcp.

Change-Id: I3c37c5c21af0aefb5007c5775043f7f837389c2d

commit_message:
Fixing issue when initializing saharaclient in OSTF

The problem is in code lines 281-283. To fix the issue
I made small refactoring the method _get_sahara_client()
not to use code lines 281-283

Closes-Bug: #1457451

Change-Id: I1f2adcfbd1c95a055c30ee306705ecdcf015c7c8

[{'created': '2015-05-18 17:29:37.000000000', 'message': 'fix subnet-create call for demo-net

(neutron client version: 2.5.0)

The option is --dns-nameservers not --dns_namservers and the
subnet-create subcommand expects the NETWORK and CIDR to be adjacent
args.

Change-Id: I4f776632902fd001c38ee5c8c87a213883ca87be
'}]
commit_message:
fix subnet-create call for demo-net

(neutron client version: 2.5.0)

The option is --dns-nameservers not --dns_namservers and the
subnet-create subcommand expects the NETWORK and CIDR to be adjacent
args.

Change-Id: I4f776632902fd001c38ee5c8c87a213883ca87be

This change adds a (currently unused) database function
stack_get_root_id to find the root stack ID for any stack.

Scheduler hints are moved to using Stack.root_stack_id() in this change.
Remaining uses of Stack.root_stack() will switch to using

commit_message:
Find root stack ID with database operations

This change adds a (currently unused) database function
stack_get_root_id to find the root stack ID for any stack.

Scheduler hints are moved to using Stack.root_stack_id() in this change.
Remaining uses of Stack.root_stack() will switch to using
Stack.root_stack_id() later in the series.

Change-Id: I9914b0df5af119edea6346db0d7c62124fbb1313
Partial-Bug: #1455589

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I779d8df5872887d5d8ec44012d792b59b0cf4f64

commit_message:
Replace 'balance-xor' bonding test by mixed

We can't test bonding using 'balance-xor' mode,
because current 'fuel-devops' implementation doesn't
support links aggregation on bridge side.
Replacing 'deploy_bonding_balance_xor' test by new
'deploy_bonding_mixed' test which deploys environment
using NovaNetwork+Vlan and configures three types of
bonds on nodes.

Change-Id: I4250d3c2053cb04428301dc819ce4dc33c04f72a
Partial-bug: #1319413

commit_message:
Fix 'ha_destroy_controllers'

Wait for OSTF HA checks passed before doing any action with cluster.

To get it working, pacemaker resources should be in working state.
It is checked in the https://review.openstack.org/#/c/178864/

Change-Id: If77442014d8a97ce47b7281b816ea1a35de942e3
Depends-On:https://review.openstack.org/#/c/178864/
Closes-Bug:#1457831

commit_message:
Extend verify_network() and add output of verification errors.

- Add @retry with count=2 to the method verify_network() to
  perform additional verify if an error occured from first try.

- Add logging of verification error, like it shown in UI.
  Example of the logging: http://paste.openstack.org/show/232435/

Change-Id: I84d34788e7ff2e35fb8b428604f5de069ab8b58f
Closes-Bug:#1458071

commit_message:
Fix successful deployment with all non-working monitors

*Disable timeout for command "ceph-deploy osd activate".
 Command "ceph-deploy osd activate" has its own timeout and if cluster
 is not accessible for this time, it exits with error.
*Decrease try number for "ceph-deploy osd activate", 6 is too many
 but 3 - enough.
*Fix messages "WARN: Unrecognised escape sequence"

Change-Id: I806aa3fd7a7420f02ba69470642e2bc3eb88fbd4
Partial-bug: #1457487
Closes-bug: #1442214

commit_message:
Disable rabbitmq management plugin

There is a known security issue exist in the
management plugin for RabbitMQ <3.4.3, so it
has to be disabled by default.

Closes-bug: #1450443
Closes-bug: #1455761

Change-Id: Ic01c26200f6019a8112b1c5fb04a282e64b3b3e6
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

Update the stack state as late as possible

The event and notifications do not look the stack up in
the DB so we can rely on the in memory status.

[{'created': '2015-05-14 17:50:55.000000000', 'message': "Add 'eno*' interfaces to embedded_nics

On certain systems, the embedded NICs appear as eno1, eno2, etc.
This patch adds 'eno' to 'em' and 'eth' as interface names that
should be considered embedded NICs.

Change-Id: Icc49596573bdbb8af25f934a647f0a2ab82adaa5
"}]
commit_message:
Add 'eno*' interfaces to embedded_nics

On certain systems, the embedded NICs appear as eno1, eno2, etc.
This patch adds 'eno' to 'em' and 'eth' as interface names that
should be considered embedded NICs.

Change-Id: Icc49596573bdbb8af25f934a647f0a2ab82adaa5

commit_message:
Do not verify requirements on extension loading

The heat gate is broken due to other libraries pinning
on pbr<1.0

Stevedore extension loading currently has verify_requirements=True.
This change removes this to use the default of False. Loading extensions
is likely the wrong place to be enforcing requirements versions of
libraries that heat depends on, so lets not do it.

This is likely to also improve heat robustness for deployments with
inconsistent dependencies, not just this current heat breakage.

Change-Id: Ifee37e00412e824eead9ba1435ea5a328ff3df58
Closes-Bug: #1458399

their own requirements when they start up and die if there is no
match. We can maybe constrain keystone to itself in a virtualenv
with USE_VENV=True when setting up the devstack.

Maybe.

This is testing that.

commit_message:
Run functional tests using virtualenvs in devstack

The functional tests are failing because keystone scripts traverse
their own requirements when they start up and die if there is no
match. Since we wish to use requirements that are uncapped we can
constrain the impact of other requirements setting USE_VENV=True
when setting up the devstack.

Gnocchi will be run its own virtualenv as well. The call to
install_gnocchi is replaced with stack_install_service gnocchi which
does the necessary environment variable setting to ensure that pip
will use the virtualenv when doing installs.

Depends-On: I3e7ac39eb43cdc4f656e0c90f3bfb23545722aef
Change-Id: Ib1e0cd087d11b317193d75110795e70a9f828a60

commit_message:
Image properties in scenario tests

Some images require additional properties.
This change adds dictionary option "img_properties"
to the "scenario" config section.
For example, to work with Parallels Containers, specify vm_mode:
img_properties = vm_mode:exe

By occasion, we fix handling properties in _image_create in scenario/manager.py:
disk_format is an x-image-meta-* option, and kernel_id, ramdisk_id are properties.

Change-Id: I2d3714eb899faad67a867a630c1d72d1fd8ee74f

commit_message:
Replace ci.o.o links with docs.o.o/infra

The http://ci.openstack.org/ documentation site has been deprecated,
replaced by redirects to corresponding paths within
http://docs.openstack.org/infra/ where other Project Infrastructure
documentation already resides.

commit_message:
Add networking-ofagent repo to Neutron

According to procedure defined in [1], this patch proposes Neutron
to embrace networking-ofagent within its fold. This project is about
providing an alternative L2 mechanism using node-local OpenFlow
controllers.

For more information on networking-ofagent:
    https://github.com/stackforge/networking-ofagent

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/doc/source/devref/sub_projects.rst

Change-Id: Id186c383092e8478668a8797446320c41a69fffc

commit_message:
Replace suds test dependency with suds-jurko

suds-jurko is actively maintained (latest commit in december 2014) and supports
Python 3, whereas suds doesn't seem to be maintained anymore (last release in
2010).

suds-jurko is a drop-in replacement for suds, both packages provide the same
Python module.

This change depends on the same change for oslo.vmware:
"Use suds-jurko on Python 2".

Blueprint nova-python3
Depends-On: I699c65e4abd607ea6f377d86c45fd609569f3c2b
Change-Id: I453ce915a31ca473edb52456be66d544349d571e

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-22 00:13:04.000000000', 'message': "Catch common Exception in container conductor

Currently, docker client and docker_client in Magnum don't handler connection
exceptions, if connection exceptions come out, no handler in conductor, so
the rpc api call will wait until timeout.

I don't find better place to handler this, because conductor only take care
of errors.APIError, instead of just catch common Exception and raise
ContainerException.

Closes-Bug: #1457366
Change-Id: Ifd2485a161ba53ef3a067eba0fe64a6548ce6637
"}, {'created': '2015-05-22 06:25:54.000000000', 'message': "Catch common Exception in container conductor

Currently, docker client and docker_client in Magnum don't handler connection
exceptions, if connection exceptions come out, no handler in conductor, so
the rpc api call will wait until timeout.

Catch common exception in _find_container_by_name and raise ContainerException,
this will notify api service exception happened, so api service won't get
time out error.

Besides, add 3 test cases for _find_container_by_name.

Closes-Bug: #1457366
Change-Id: Ifd2485a161ba53ef3a067eba0fe64a6548ce6637
"}, {'created': '2015-05-22 13:30:04.000000000', 'message': "Catch common Exception in container conductor

Currently, docker client and docker_client in Magnum don't handler connection
exceptions, if connection exceptions come out, no handler in conductor, so
the rpc api call will wait until timeout.

This patch adds a new decorator to wrap method in container conductor method
to catch common exception and raise ContainerException to avoid api service
get time out error.

After applied this path, connection error will be like this:

taget@taget-ThinkStation-P300:~$ magnum container-create < container.json

commit_message:
Catch common Exception in container conductor

Currently, docker client and docker_client in Magnum dones't handle connection
exceptions, if connection exceptions come out, no handlers in conductor, so
the rpc api call will wait until timeout error and report client as rpc
timeout errors.

This patch adds a new decorator to wrap method in container conductor methods
to catch common exception and raise ContainerException to avoid api service
get time out error.

After applied this path, connection error will be like this:

taget@taget-ThinkStation-P300:~$ magnum container-create < container.json
ERROR: Docker internal Error: ('Connection aborted.', error(111, 'ECONNREFUSED
 ... ')) (HTTP 500)

Besides, add 1 new test cases for _find_container_by_name.

Closes-Bug: #1457366
Change-Id: Ifd2485a161ba53ef3a067eba0fe64a6548ce6637

commit_message:
Fix a bug in scaleutils.truncate_desired

The cluster's current min_size/max_size should be used to truncate
desired capacity only when new min_size/max_size parameter is not
given. There is bug in current implementation for this logic and
this patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I132181fed57d3941ac6131e8b284ad17859e2222
Closes-Bug: #1456124

commit_message:
Describe basic checks and recovery steps for AMQP issues.

This brings new section into the ops guide, which describes
how to check and recover AMQP issues in Mirantis OpenStack environments
deployed by Fuel.

Closes-bug: #1456082

Change-Id: I73e6d4fce336911406272f8c537f7003fdb1b5bb
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

Two changes are made:

1. user_reference module has been replaced by profile module in
   latest release of python-openstacksdk. This patch makes some
   modifications in senlin sdk driver to follow this change.

2. Set verify_requirements parameter to default False when creating
   stevedore ExtensionManager. That is the reason why the gate broke
   for pbr version confliction in stevedore. So let's make this change
   temporarily.

Note: these two changes need to be made in the same patch. Otherwise
there will be circular dependency.

Change-Id: I83f3895c38acd14ec1f8a6f11cb89b3ce4d029d9
"}]
commit_message:
Replace sdk user_reference module with profile

Two changes are made:

1. user_reference module has been replaced by profile module in
   latest release of python-openstacksdk. This patch makes some
   modifications in senlin sdk driver to follow this change.

2. Set verify_requirements parameter to default False when creating
   stevedore ExtensionManager. That is the reason why the gate broke
   for pbr version confliction in stevedore. So let's make this change
   temporarily.

Note: these two changes need to be made in the same patch. Otherwise
there will be circular dependency.

Change-Id: I83f3895c38acd14ec1f8a6f11cb89b3ce4d029d9

commit_message:
Ensure the rabbit-fence daemon started and respawned

W/o this fix, if the daemon crashed, it
would remain stopped. Also, the rabbit fence
daemon will crash on start, when there is no
/var/run/rabbitmq piddir exist.

The solution is
* add the respawn option to
the daemon's upstart (TODO for Centos inittab)
* and ensure the piddir
created by upstart/init.d before starting the daemon.

This also requires to add the rabbitmq and
fuel-rabbit-fence packages as a dependency.

Closes-bug: #1456791

Change-Id: I4e71eb9e4aa4ff3b877aa89a37d82215740aaeab
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

Hide remove rule if no rule inserted in FW policy

Hide 'remove rule' row action in firewall policies, if no rule is inserted in it.

Add keystone benchmark scenarios for roles

Add keystone assign_and_remove_role scenario.
  API covered roles.add_user_role, roles.remove_user_role

Add keystone create_and_delete_role scenario.
  API covered roles.create, roles.delete

Add keystone create_and_list_user_roles scenario.
  API covered roles.create, roles.list

commit_message:
Follow i18n guidelines in LIO target

In LIO target some logging instances do not follow i18n guidelines
related to delayed string interpolation.

Change-Id: Ie184725ea9d83d676612ec82ea56013c0f15eed4

commit_message:
PXE/ISCSI: Call partx after partioning the disk

The _wait_for_disk_to_become_available function from
common/disk_partitioner.py calls fuser to check if the is not being held
by another process, but it doesn't actually check if the partitions of the
device is available after the disk is partitioned. This patch adds a call
to partx -u to make the kernel re-read the partition table of the device
and then list the partitions to verify if they are really available.

Closes-Bug: #1403887
Change-Id: I880ef1120f98e32d802f52db36955da95f7daeb7

commit_message:
VMware: add VirtualVmxnet3 to hw_vif_model

Commit I97147f8e0f749ee76f17569191e45eb520f7c88f added VirtualVmxnet3
to the list of supported network models.  The glance compute metadata
definition should reflect that change.

Change-Id: I0e363233582584d5d7a62477603795a237f49b5c

commit_message:
Tests don't override default auth methods/plugins

The tests were overriding the default auth methods and plugins even
when the defaults work fine. The tests should use the defaults when
it makes sense so that the test config is easier to change.

bp stevedore

Change-Id: Iefb98d90f22dd0852a2b894c48db1a570bd3d4bf

commit_message:
Correct tests setting auth methods to a non-list

The auth methods config option is a list, not a string. In most
cases the tests were setting the auth methods when the test
didn't need to, so the line was just removed.

Change-Id: I0f0cbfe84bc37c8a0bc5a3b2b3669c86e6b5996f

(5 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8300, 'date': '2015-04-28 06:23:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

If I understand you correctly, you will first add request id to the userauthplugin (get the request id from env['openstack.request_id'] and set to the plugin in AuthProtocol->__call__ method), then in the keystoneclient session, you will get the request id from the plugin and add it to the request header in the session's request method.

I think there is a need to encrypt X-Openstack-Request-ID header in the session's request method (otherwise a malicious user can pass same request id for each api messing up log messages) then decrypt it on the receiving end and use it further down the line (request_id oslo.middleware) and if it fails, then it will create a new request id.

I understand, changes to the keystoneclient is out of this scope, but I would like to confirm how the keystone client will use this X-Openstack-Request-ID header from auth plugin."}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-05-20 19:37:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

I don't think encryption the request ID is something auth middleware needs to worry about as it is not generating a new one. standardize service to service requests.

commit_message:
Remove simplejson dependency

In addition to removing an unnecessary dependency, this closes another
hole that was allowing raw bytes to appear in user-facing messages.

DevStack: Remove SOA/NS checks

Akamai/DynECT will "randomly" pick a NS from the
set to use, meaning this check will fail needlessly

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: I040ee1b2e14ba5c36de85cb042bbaff41dbbaf3a

commit_message:
Removed the '_safe_message' variable from the API exceptions

The variable _safe_message is linked to logic that is either no
longer used or not implemented. Removing the variable is a part
of improving the exception message by using 1 source to generate
the exception message

Partially Implements: blueprint improve-error-message-details-for-usability

Change-Id: Ied1acf22790cdedad685990fc628462d51b1477e

commit_message:
ngReorg - align module names with directory

This commit aligns module names with their directory
structure.

This is one step in a larger effort to restructure the Angular
source. See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176152/ for the
full set of planned changes.

Change-Id: I3f48ebaef23d6249983f33b1a4710cc1fe3ef789
Partial-Bug: #1454880

[{'created': '2015-05-13 12:04:18.000000000', 'message': 'Restructure builds to allow more flexibility

As a restructure, nothing is changed from the original behaviour and
naming despite the file structure changing. The new structure is:

docker/${base_distro}/${type}/${container}

base_distro == centos, ubuntu, fedora, etc
type == source, binary, rdo

type rdo is a symlink to binary for backwards compatibility

Two new flags are added to the build-all script to support the ability
to support different base distros and a flag to support binary or source
containers.

There are several added folders that are empty to hold the directory
structure for future containers of these types.

Change-Id: Ifc7bac0d827470f506c8b5c004a833da9ce13b90
'}, {'created': '2015-05-13 12:23:41.000000000', 'message': 'Restructure builds to allow more flexibility

As a restructure, nothing is changed from the original behaviour and
naming despite the file structure changing. The only modified file is
the tools/build-all-docker-images script. The symlinks to build had to
be updated as well generating "deleted" and "new_file".

The new structure is:

docker/${base_distro}/${type}/${container}

base_distro == centos, ubuntu, fedora, etc
type == source, binary, rdo

type rdo is a symlink to binary for backwards compatibility

Two new flags are added to the build-all script to support the ability
to support different base distros and a flag to support binary or source
containers.

There are several added folders that are empty to hold the directory
structure for future containers of these types.

Example:
./build-all-docker-images -b ubuntu -t binary
kollaglue/ubuntu-binary-ceilometer-base

./build-all-docker-images -b centos -t source
kollaglue/centos-source-ceilometer-base

./build-all-docker-images
kollaglue/centos-rdo-ceilometer-base

Change-Id: Ifc7bac0d827470f506c8b5c004a833da9ce13b90

naming despite the file structure changing. The only modified file is
the tools/build-all-docker-images script. The symlinks to build had to
be updated as well generating "deleted" and "new_file".

The new structure is:

docker/${base_distro}/${type}/${container}

base_distro == centos, ubuntu, fedora, etc
type == source, binary, rdo

type rdo is a symlink to binary for backwards compatibility

Two new flags are added to the build-all script to support the ability
to support different base distros and a flag to support binary or source
containers.

There are several added folders that are empty to hold the directory
structure for future containers of these types.

Example:
./build-all-docker-images -b ubuntu -t binary
kollaglue/ubuntu-binary-ceilometer-base

./build-all-docker-images -b centos -t source
kollaglue/centos-source-ceilometer-base

./build-all-docker-images
kollaglue/centos-rdo-ceilometer-base

cd docker/centos/rdo/ceilometer/ceilometer-base
./build --release
kollaglue/centos-rdo-ceilometer-base

commit_message:
Restructure builds to allow more flexibility

As a restructure, nothing is changed from the original behaviour and
naming despite the file structure changing. The symlinks to build had
to be updated generating lots of "deleted" and "new_file".

The new structure is:

docker/${base_distro}/${type}/${container}

base_distro == centos, ubuntu, fedora, etc
type == source, binary, rdo

type rdo is a symlink to binary for backwards compatibility

Two new flags are added to the build-all script to support the ability
to support different base distros and a flag to support binary or source
containers.

There are several added folders that are empty to hold the directory
structure for future containers of these types.

To use a prefix other than centos-rdo- you can set PREFIX in the toplevel
directory .buildconf file

Change-Id: Ifc7bac0d827470f506c8b5c004a833da9ce13b90

commit_message:
"Report a bug" link in HTML manuals automatically fills in bug's tag

The "Report a bug" link in the HTML manuals populate information about the page.
Since manuals within openstack-manuals project have their own tag within
launchpad, this patch automatically tags the bug using a tag defined in conf.py.

Change-Id: I3c9214a4f5a00648d325b4acaa493057ab0e4821
Closes-Bug: #1342373

commit_message:
Kazoo had a new release with fixes projects would like

Some of the things addressed:

- Locks for tooz that work better
- Native eventlet handler support
- Ability to close a client (silently closing
  if it was never started in the first part)
  for taskflow

Others at the following:

https://github.com/python-zk/kazoo/blob/2.1/CHANGES.rst

Change-Id: I6146ed0aa94a7d361235582948c0ece07b08bfd9

commit_message:
Kazoo 2.1 has a bug which is breaking tooz gate

This bug is opened at https://github.com/python-zk/kazoo/issues/315

The PR fix is at https://github.com/python-zk/kazoo/pull/316

Until that merges and is released reduce the required version to a
known set that is known to work (vs one that is not).

If I understand this code correctly, we are moving to a multi-threaded conductor. I do not understand why. Can't we rely on heat for the concurrent orchestration work we want to do? Is there a scale-out bay implementation that keeps our conductors single threaded? What trade-offs need to be considered here?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-15 02:04:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-magnum-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/74/172774/4/check/gate-magnum-pep8/2adc59a/ : SUCCESS in 1m 57s
- gate-magnum-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/74/172774/4/check/gate-magnum-docs/20fbdbb//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 05s
- gate-magnum-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/74/172774/4/check/gate-magnum-python27/5a0793d/ : FAILURE in 2m 26s
- check-functional-dsvm-magnum http://logs.openstack.org/74/172774/4/check/check-functional-dsvm-magnum/b5109e2/ : SUCCESS in 27m 00s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-04-15 05:16:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Adrian,

I don't rely on heat for concurrency for the reasons below:
* Need to keep the heat stack and DB in sync during each conductor operation (create/update/delete). For a typically conductor operation, it appears to be this pattern: call heat -> write DB -> call heat -> call heat -> write DB ... In the case of multiple conductors, there are a lot of possibilities for the linearity of execution. E.g. A call heat -> B call Heat -> B write DB -> A write DB .. Such executions could lead Magnum to an inconsistent state.
* K8s/swarns/container operations may need concurrent control as well, and it is impossible to rely on heat to achieve that.

I move to multi-threaded conductor for the reasons below:
* I want to ensure each conductor operation is atomic. It looks the simplest and intuitive way to do this is to lock down the bay during the entire operation (until the heat polling completes). If signal-threaded, the lock will block the conductor. In multi-threaded, the lock will block the bay which is more preferable.

For alternative single-threaded implementations:
* There is none. Even the current (single conductor) implementation is multi-threaded (with single thread to call heat and spawn a thread to poll).
* The proposed implementation is simply to lock down the entire operation (therefore use a thread to execute it to avoid blocking the conductor). Maybe there are alternative implementations exist for placing a smaller chunk of codes to the thread.

Trade-off:
* Main advantages of the proposed approach are (i) simple to verify the correctness of synchronization/concurrency and (ii) higher conductor throughput.
* Main disadvantage is that users won't know stack failures right away (e.g. magnum bay-create won't show error response anymore if the stack creation fails, users need to query it by magnum bay-show)."}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-04-15 06:09:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-04-15 10:55:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

My previous concerns have been addressed, so I am changing my vote to No Score (0). I am curious about this statement:

"Main disadvantage is that users won't know stack failures right away (e.g. magnum bay-create won't show error response anymore if the stack creation fails, users need to query it by magnum bay-show)."

Can you explain this a bit more, please? Is there any way we can think of that would poll the stack for errors, and raise them (perhaps after some reasonable delay) if they are detected? Is this because the stack operations were previously handled in a synchronous way with respect to the user, and now they are asynchronous?'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-04-15 10:57:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Also, the py27 gate test seems to be tripping on a "pkg_resources.ContextualVersionConflict". See:

http://logs.openstack.org/74/172774/4/check/gate-magnum-python27/5a0793d/console.html#_2015-04-15_01_33_37_977

I expect you are already aware of this, but wanted to mention it just in case.'}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-04-15 16:42:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Adrian, exactly. That is because the stack call is changed from synchronized to asynchronized. That means the main thread won't wait for the heat call to return, so unable to poll the errors.

We could detect the stack errors in some ways. That basically means stepping back to the single-threaded solution (since the main thread needs to wait the heat call to return), which has pros and cons. The obvious cons is that it blocks the main thread, thus blocking current conductor. At this patch, each conductor needs to ping each other for healthiness check. Therefore, if one conductor is blocked, the ping will be blocked, which in term blocking other conductors.

A solution could be validating the inputs in single thread before spawning a thread to call heat. Then, some stack errors can be detected earlier. After spawning a thread, any stack error will be considered as runtime error, which has to be detected in 'magnum show ...'. That's like 'heat stack-create ... ' returns 4XX response if validation fails. Otherwise, it returns 2XX and users need to call 'heat stack-show ...' to detect runtime errors."}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-04-15 18:52:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

With that said, I think we can achieve the goal step-by-step. Here is the proposal.
* I can modify this patch to use single thread to call heat, but lock it down to ensure its correctness.
* After kilo release, I will submit another patch to activate the multi-threading.

Then, in kilo release, magnum basically supports multiple conductors, although it will has concurrency issue (which seems to be minor if magnum is not production-ready). After the release, I will fully explore any potential alternative to the multi-thread implementation. What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 7049, 'date': '2015-04-16 02:06:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-16 02:40:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
[WIP] Utilize baylock for conductor horizontal-scale

The bay operations below will be executed with exclusive lock.
When a bay is locked, it will reject other operations until the
current operation finishes.

* bay-create
* bay-update
* bay-delete

Co-Authored-By: Steven Dake <stdake@cisco.com>

Change-Id: I4cf1a96b1abc9def914d2c26103646722a4436e8
Partial-Implements: blueprint horizontal-scale

commit_message:
Update for pip 7.0.0

The trusted host option when installing from a domain that is not
https is no longer optional. This change adds a domain variable to
the groupvars/all.yml and ensures that the get-pip.py installation
process is using the `--trusted-host`` flag and is pointed back at
the domain name used in the "openstack_upstream_domain".

Change-Id: I18539cf4b8790c096d44a0de4985b9d4293d95e3
(cherry picked from commit 473881dcae890fd8520f5bb1777e907d6e8f3abd)

commit_message:
Add notes about kernel support for geneve.

Note that Kernels prior to 3.18 did not include geneve support
natively.  Also link to the OVS FAQ document that covers this issue
in more detail.

Change-Id: I35c4538ffe78208ba1b61d1de30372f8be6f799e

commit_message:
Fix common misspellings

Wikipedia's list of common misspellings [1] has a machine-readable
version.  This patch fixes those misspellings mentioned in the list
which don't have multiple right variants (as e.g. "accension", which can
be both "accession" and "ascension"), such misspellings are left
untouched.  The list of changes was manually re-checked for false
positives.

[1] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Lists_of_common_misspellings/For_machines

Change-Id: I44d53a807a6d2e9910daab939f4c0b7768c07ad9
Signed-off-by: Martin Kletzander <mkletzan@redhat.com>

)

commit_message:
make registering a cli opt on a filter object work.

Change the behaviour of ConfigFilter.register_cli_opt to:

1. If the opt is already registered before parsing, then registering
just import it.
2. if the opt is not registered before, then raise an exception named

CliOptRegisteredError.
By adding this modification, the behaviour of
ConfigFilter.register_cli_opt looks more consistent to
ConfigOpts.register_cli_opt. The solution to the question mentioned in
Bug#1366946 should be like this:

from oslo_config import cfg
from oslo_config import cfgfilter

import sys

c = cfg.CONF
c.register_cli_opt(
cfg.BoolOpt('myflag',
default=False,
help='turn on myflag',
)
)
c(sys.argv[1:])

f = cfgfilter.ConfigFilter(c)
f.register_cli_opt(
cfg.BoolOpt('myflag',
default=False,
help='turn on myflag',
)
)

print f.myflag

Closes-Bug: #1366946
Change-Id: I94df9409f72807461370b4aaf8eb2543c52a89bb

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-13 09:43:55.000000000', 'message': "timeutils: utcnow() returns a value with a timezone

utcnow() used to return a non-timezone-aware timezone, which is terrible
as there is then no way to know if it's a local time object or a UTC
time zone object.
This patch changes utcnow() so it carries that information in the
datetime object.

It also fixes a bunch of function calls that were not normalizing the
datetime object before using them, resulting in potential errors or
mistakes.

Change-Id: Ib098ef16063d97e37ff2b9a0fc934f67fd9ed5f3

commit_message:
timeutils: utcnow() can return a value with a timezone

utcnow() used to return a non-timezone-aware timezone, which is terrible
as there is then no way to know if it's a local time object or a UTC
time zone object. This patch changes utcnow() so it can carry that
information in the datetime object.

Change-Id: Ib098ef16063d97e37ff2b9a0fc934f67fd9ed5f3

Two things:

2) Im not sure eventlet monkeypatches syscall calls and therefore this might block randomly.'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2014-12-03 23:01:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Why not make the address for the python logging syslog handler configurable via oslo.log when using use_syslog = True. Then you can be portable without shipping a different handler.

I think this is important to keep python logging configs sane across deployments. As soon as you start shipping a non default syslog handler you will have some number of deployments using the non default handler and another set using the handler that ships with OpenStack turned on via use_syslog.

Having two is just twice as many things that can fail when really all we need is better config.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-12-09 18:58:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-2

greg, you mean a serious improvement in avoiding race conditions in code never designed to switch context at log time? Since the vast majority of OpenStack is not thread safe.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-02-26 09:34:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

As far I known eventlet and the old syslog handler class is already and still broken, due to an (still unfixed) eventlet bug:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.log/+bug/1076466

commit_message:
Replace RFCSysLogHandler by a syslog() based one

Rather than using the Python provided logging module that reimplents the
whole syslog protocol and pointing it to /dev/log (which is not
portable), we use the system calls from the syslog module, which are
portable and default to the behaviour we actually want.

Closes-Bug: 1385295
Closes-Bug: 1391428

Change-Id: I39a36316bd8778831b1bd5e7c5e2e12ede062a37

commit_message:
Improve logging to debug invalid "extra_specs" entries

When volume creation fails due to invalid extra_specs entry, its hard
to find a mismatch between extra_specs and capabilities exposed by
multiple hosts. This additional log printings will help to detect a root
cause of the failure.

Change-Id: Ibca56c8ad4cc473ad35f1c79e9892acbf08bf5f1

commit_message:
Replace ci.o.o links with docs.o.o/infra

The http://ci.openstack.org/ documentation site has been deprecated,
replaced by redirects to corresponding paths within
http://docs.openstack.org/infra/ where other Project Infrastructure
documentation already resides.

Change-Id: Ia914d1802b57f7101dd86b2098857dd714763dd1

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Change-Id: Ic912ba2ca89754bc795e3135f037da138f134a1f

commit_message:
Drop explicit suds dependency

we should just use what oslo.vmware requires. Transitive
dependency should be enough for Nova.

Remove a few imports in a test case to pass the nova
policy of "if any explicit import then need an entry
in requirements".

Also remove tests relating to suds as oslo.vmware uses
suds and any of these tests should be there instead.

Co-Authored-By: Victor Stinner <vstinner@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I28f29d3e5745c21b99dc0cf9eb0cfe4f95dffd17

commit_message:
Do not crash on homedir mkdir

Glanceclient is trying to create ~/.glanceclient, and crashes if it can't
do that. In some environment (for example, when building the package
under Jenkins), writing on $HOME is simply not allowed, and Glanceclient
can simply ignore it. This patch allows the mkdir() to fail, which fixes
the issue.

Closes-Bug: #1446096
Change-Id: Ib3591fb4e54ccd2fe63a1a4815551ac10ef5b961

commit_message:
Remove erroneous info about VNC resizing in horizon

According to https://ask.openstack.org/en/question/9351, resizing of the
VNC window is automatic and doesn't need configuration modifications.

Remove erroneous content from the config-ref.

Change-Id: I5c33f4c1d7c768f3a4eb3916dca73c0d1f77b833

commit_message:
Removed statement that SSH injection is not supported

SSH injection is now supported for VMware-backed OpenStack deployments.

Change-Id: Iec2bbc5d1e627e6f84c0f5867878a6828104abde
Closes-Bug: #1457997

I don't think this is going to be a good idea. pbr has custom testr code that is used by this entry point, I'm pretty sure it's on purpose. If it's not, the code should then be deleted as well."}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-09-29 15:14:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Let me explain what I thought before submitting the patch.

This patch removes "testr" command which invokes  "pbr.testr_command:Testr", but the same command is also registered by setup-hooks "pbr.hooks.setup_hook". pbr.hooks.commands registers 'pbr.packaging.TestrTest' (as "testr" command) and TestrTest finally calls pbr.testr_command.Testr.run(). Thus even if this patch removes distutils.command "testr", there is no changes. We still have "testr" command in setup.py. If --help-commands always requires testrepository with pbr, testrepository should be added to the requirement list.

Thought?
The only difference is that distutils.command always requires testrepository but the way via pbr.hooks.commands only registers "testr" command when testrepository module is available. We can't run setup.py testr command if testrepository is not instsalled, so there is no difference as a result.

According to the above observation, I think this change is safe.

If we don't use this approach, there are two ways remaining: (1) to remove testr related code completely, or (2) to make "setup.py --help-command" completely broken with pbr (unless testrepository is installed). (1) loses pbr testr test and (2) makes many users of python modules using pbr frustrated.'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2014-09-30 12:09:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

I don't know this enough to have a good opinion, but you sound to have good arguments so I withdraw my -1 :)"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-10-02 17:29:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Make setup.py --help-commands work without testrepository

testr command is registered by pbr.hooks.commands if
testrepository is installed, so there is no need to
setup the entry point in setup.cfg.

Change-Id: I95aae12d1ac810b6d1d09b71f2a0d87be5ccb6ab
Closes-Bug: #1375048

commit_message:
Update LPAR feed to exclude mgmt partition

The PowerVM API introduced a new parameter to determine the management
partition.  This should be excluded from the operations for VMs.  This
change set updates the nova code such that it excludes that partition
from VM feeds.

Change-Id: I800e0df774403ebc62ad8a5c5df0e77bb0017b25

commit_message:
Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* basic_swift_spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.

Change-Id: I745fa76b2b36b0dbada83260fedffc4ee60f9c03
Closes-bug: #1444736

[{'created': '2015-05-22 12:00:17.000000000', 'message': "Ignore lint quoted boolean warning

The $::selinux global comes from factor, and gets stringified with
Puppet 3.x.  Because of this we want to suppress the lint warning since
it's actually what we want to do.

Change-Id: Id18a027c8bda8ae465cbcd9517ea79e07a868bf8

commit_message:
Ignore lint quoted boolean warning

The $::selinux global comes from factor, and gets stringified with
Puppet 3.x.  Because of this we want to suppress the lint warning since
it's actually what we want to do.

Change-Id: Id18a027c8bda8ae465cbcd9517ea79e07a868bf8

commit_message:
Remove updated property check from V2

When updating an image using V2 the client checks whether a property is
being changed, if the property is not being changed the the client won't
send it to glance. The server then doesn't raise reserved properties
errors because it won't get the update for that property. It should
be up to the server to check whether the properties from an updated
image have changed.

Fixes-bug: #1307412

Change-Id: Ia4b2d791926c77b20deacc22cf59f3af00f7407b

commit_message:
GlusterFS: Renaming test case to test_mount_glusterfs

With the patch [1], GlusterFS is now using mount method in
RemoteFsClient. That method mounts a gluster share only if it has
not already been mounted.

So, having test case name as
test_mount_glusterfs_should_mount_correctly, doesn't make sense now.
This patch changes its name to 'test_mount_glusterfs'.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/165424/

Change-Id: I33c16a8315a11fc16ab478d667490f3f73002ee8

commit_message:
ovs-agent: prevent ARP requests with faked IP addresses

This patch extends the existing ARP protection to ensure
that ARP requests also have valid IP addresses.

Closes-Bug: 1456333

Change-Id: I0b2ba21611c9fd9e304bce8cfb00259db1dceaa2

> Hum... So you did not activate the rule that is why pep8 do not fail.

Using this hacking new check, tox -e pep8 fails. Jenkins succeeded because I added dependencies to the 3 changes fixing the usage of all dict.iter*() methods.

> I do not think you can have this separated to the change made in the base code the aim is to avoid future add between change and hacking rule.

For practical reasons, I prefer to have separated changes. My other changes are generated by the sixer tool, so it's easy to recreate them from scratch in case of a complex conflict, and to fix newly added code.

Joe Gordon looks to prefer running Python 3 tests than adding a few hacking rules."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-05-22 21:01:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Detect the following patterns which are not compatible with Python 3:

* d.iteritems()
* d.iterkeys()
* d.itervalues()

Explicitly ignore files using SQLAlchemy objects because these objects
only have an iteritems() method, no items() method. six.iteritems() must
not be used in these files.

This patch is based on Icc3875d6bf97ab10011c17c89244564045efc759
written by Cyril Roelandt.

commit_message:
Add hacking rule to detect Python 3 compat issues

Detect the following patterns which are not compatible with Python 3:

* d.iteritems()
* d.iterkeys()
* d.itervalues()

Explicitly ignore files using SQLAlchemy objects because these objects
only have an iteritems() method, no items() method. six.iteritems() must
not be used in these files.

This patch is based on Icc3875d6bf97ab10011c17c89244564045efc759
written by Cyril Roelandt.

Co-Authored-By: Cyril Roelandt <cyril.roelandt@enovance.com>

Removed use of contextlib.nested call from codebase, as it has been
deprecated since Python 2.7.

There are also known issues with contextlib.nested that were addressed
by the native support for multiple "with" variables. For instance, if

commit_message:
Remove use of contextlib.nested

Removed use of contextlib.nested call from codebase, as it has been
deprecated since Python 2.7.

There are also known issues with contextlib.nested that were addressed
by the native support for multiple "with" variables. For instance, if
the first object is created but the second one throws an exception,
the first object's __exit__ is never called. For more information see
https://docs.python.org/2/library/contextlib.html#contextlib.nested
contextlib.nested is also not compatible with Python 3.

Multi-patch set for easier chunks. This one addresses the
neutron/plugins/ml2 directory.

Line continuation markers (e.g. '\') had to be used or syntax
errors were thrown. While using parentheses is the preferred way
for multiple line statements, but in case of long with statements
backslashes are acceptable.

Partial-Bug: 1428424
Change-Id: I7bbe4cec511125b4b2c954aa93e2d9ff6871b9e0

commit_message:
WIP: Object pinning

Do not merge.  This is a PoC to demonstrate how to pin objects
to a given milestone version, so that it can be converted to the
correct object version before it is sent over RPC.  This PoC
uses the Snapshot object as an example, since it is the most
complete so far.

Change-Id: Id5e0c9551b34a9a1374e69e1e17a1ee25e218cd4

commit_message:
IPAM reference driver

An alternate pluggable IPAM implementation from the built-in one
in db_base_plugin_v2.
Modifies IPAM interface to allow passing context to driver and
introduces new interface method 'associate_neutron_subnet'.

Implements blueprint reference-ipam-driver

Change-Id: I2e1e9fc7994bf1157bcd34b7ea500eb30c61d9ab

commit_message:
Use namespace names in NetcatTester

Currently NetcatTester requests namespace IPWrapper instances as
client/server_namespace arguments but functional tests commonly use
namespace names as arguments not IPWrapper instances (because IPWrapper
is cheap to instantiate) and NetcatTester needs only namespace names.

This change requests names as NetcatTester client/server_namespace
arguments in order to simplify NetcatTester and its use.

Change-Id: Ic4a297efdeaef00e70892d1c871ce1c9174055b8

commit_message:
Handle http response code 404 properly

Any operation "wait_for_delete" expects that exception with http code "404"
will be raised.
Different python clients return this code with different names of attribute -
either "code" or "http_status".
But function "rally/benchmark/utils.py:get_from_manager" does not expect
the latter case and raises general exception "exceptions.GetResourceFailure"
instead of expected "exceptions.GetResourceNotFound".
So, fix mentioned function and related unit test that was asserting
wrong thing.

Change-Id: I0430ed8a3e9308e8f4a245b4c68e8d7f1f0bd02d
Closes-Bug: #1457882
