- gate-rally-dsvm-glance http://logs.openstack.org/21/165321/3/check/gate-rally-dsvm-glance/649fd78/ : SUCCESS in 32m 05s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-03-18 12:58:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

I'm concerned about this change based on some behaviour I've seen.

We had been hitting some issues with glance client (invoked by Nova) leaking file descriptors:

 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156975

We tried changing http_keepalive to False in order to have the server tear down the socket and prevent an eventual 'too many file descriptors' issue.

While setting to False did workaround the leaking socket issue (which has since been fixed) it was unusable due to the side effect of causing corrupted image downloads.

We tried two configurations: one where the SSL termination was done by stunnel (this is the standard TripleO configuration), and another where SSL termination was done by HA Proxy. In both cases, downloads of 'large' (> 200 MB) images were corrupted. Most of the image would get downloaded, but the final part would not.

So, while not necessarily an intrinsic Glance issue, the fact that this change will break image downloads for several deployment scenarios (including another OpenStack project - TripleO, when https is enabled) is problematic."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2015-03-19 03:40:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hmm interesting..So to me that means actually we don't have a way to resolve stock leak issue for glance, finally we still have to turn the keepalive option on for normal image download case. Abhishek do you have any thoughts as the original fix provider?"}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2015-03-19 06:46:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Zhi, Stuart,

Not sure but can this patch will fix that download issue?
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119132/

eventlet socket timeout allows closing idle client connections after a period of configured time.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-03-19 12:17:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Zhi Yan

> So to me that means actually we don't have a way to resolve stock leak issue for glance

Specifically which leak issue? Thanks.

@Abhishek

It's not obvious to me that 119132 would prevent the download issue. (It does help in terms of ensuring that idle sockets are eventually closed.)

Rather than just disabling http keepalive, what we may want is eventlet to have something like apache's KeepAliveTimeout (http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.2/mod/core.html#keepalive). That would allow leaving keepalive on (which is probably a good thing, for example, when listing many pages of images) but allows timing out of the persistent connection if it hasn't been re-used for a new request in a specified period of time."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2015-03-20 07:35:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Stuart, I mean this issue https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1361360 , which was fixed by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130839 before. The reason to me  of why do this change was mentioned at here https://review.openstack.org/#/c/162964/2/glance/common/wsgi.py , as an inline comment, btw. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2015-03-20 10:30:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Zhi Yan,

Thanks for clarifying.

There are two similar situations where a client connection can be held open indefinitely.

1) A client makes a request, the server completes the request; http keepalive is 'True' so the server doesn't tear down the connection (it relies on the client to do so) but the client fails to ever close the connection.

2) A client connects to the server, and just holds an open connection, ie never actually makes a legal request.

In the case of (1) the user will require an authenticated token. In the case of (2) the user can just do 'nc host port' to establish a connection -- no credentials required.

Even if http_keepalive is set to False that does nothing to help case (2).

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119132/ can help with both cases. But has the problem that if you set the client_socket_timeout value too agressively (ie too low) then you may close a socket that has stalled temporarily, eg during the middle of a download.

It does seem that to keep the good aspect of http keepalive (eg for recycling sockets when listing large numbers of images) while preventing sockets being kept open by the client we need something like Apache's KeepAliveTimeout. This would allow us to keep a reasonably high value of client_socket_timeout (ie be forgiving of stalls during downloads) but set a low value for keep alive timeout, ie close the socket fairly quickly after handling a request if no new request is received.

Based on the issues with setting keepalive to False (download corruption, potential performance hit to listing) and the fact that sockets can still be held open by (2), I'm leaning towards keeping the current default. (And maybe looking to add KeepAliveTimeout to eventlet).

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2015-05-21 21:47:41.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Set http_keepalive default value to False

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections. Hence even
after the response is sent to the client, it does not close the
client socket connection. Because of this problem, the green thread
is not released back to the pool. Setting this option to False will
avoid this leak happen. Right now it is set to True for backward
compatibility.

Changed default value of http_keepalive to False.

Change-Id: I5c72a7692e7bb0ed36613f5dbfb42142afc5bd6e
Closes-Bug: #1433435

commit_message:
Move image creation from compute api to manager

shelve_offload_time parameter is configured only on the compute nodes and
in case it is set to -2 then it is not necessary to take the snapshot of
the instance so the logic of creating image is moved from compute api to
compute manager.

Moved create_image method to compute utils package to create the image on
compute node and removed image_id from shelve_instance rpc call.

Change-Id: I2f5720b191bad1a411b35a4f6816b891e51142cc
blueprint: improve-unshelve-performance

0, offload when shelved

-2, offload partially, release CPU/Memory but retain instance files

commit_message:
Improve performance of Unshelve api

Aim of this feature is to improve the performance of unshelve instance
by eliminating downloading/copying snapshot time. All instance files will be
retained in the instance store backed by shared or non-shared storage on the
compute node when an instance is shelved.

An existing configuration parameter "shelved_offload_time" will be used here
to indicate the instance files should not be deleted.

New value will be added:
shelved_offload_time = -2

Offload partially. In this case instance files will be retained. CPU and
Memory will be released back to the hypervisor which can be used for
spawning new instances.

Added new VM state 'SHELVED_PARTIAL_OFFLOADED' and new Task state
'SHELVING_PARTIAL_OFFLOADING', so user can identify by VM status
that, instance is partially offloaded and instance files are persisted
on the host.

DocImpact:
An existing configuration parameter “shelved_offload_time" will be modified
here to indicate the instance files shouldn’t be deleted.

-1, never offload
0, offload when shelved
> 0, offload using “_poll_shelved_instances” periodic task

New value will be added
-2, offload partially, release CPU/Memory but retain instance files

Change-Id: Iedb910e6656cdefd6d668262c7ed0726dbb1475a

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-01-27 22:38:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-01-27 22:47:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This was increased to 24 hours just in 2013 because with large numbers of VMs the short timeout was causing a lot of DHCP traffic, and seems to be what might be configured in a typical production network.  I would rather add some documentation on why to choose a certain lease timeout.

Also, why did the IP of the VM change while it was up and running?  That almost sounds like a bug.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-01-27 23:15:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-01-27 23:19:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

The interval was changed in 2013 with very little discussion. This default is still 4 times the previous default.


The IPs can change because neutron ports can be updated with new IPs. A tenant might add a new subnet for re-addressing purposes and move all of the ports over to the new subnet. It's not a bug, it's just a feature that isn't used commonly, but when it is, a 24 hour lease duration sucks."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-01-27 23:59:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-01-28 00:05:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

We have to make the default a reasonable value for most deployments, and I don't think 8 minutes is long enough - some people would argue the default should be days or weeks.

We initially had it set pretty short in our public cloud, and got some complaints (and had too much DHCP traffic and large logs).  It's been at 172800 since then and not a peep from anyone, so if anything I'm biased towards longer.

Even a typical Linksys router defaults to 24 hours, from eth0.lease:

lease {
  interface "eth0";
  fixed-address 10..0.114;
  option subnet-mask 255.255.255.0;
  option routers 10.0.0.1;
  option dhcp-lease-time 86400;
...

I think discussing the default on the ML is also a better place than a patch, since there's only 2-3 people even watching this.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-28 00:41:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

- gate-neutron-pylint http://logs.openstack.org/95/150595/2/check/gate-neutron-pylint/194929b/ : SUCCESS in 4m 41s'}, {'account_id': 9820, 'date': '2015-01-28 01:01:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hi Kevin, I agree with Brian, this should be discuss in ML. 
And I think 24h is better than 8 min in production... There will be a lot of dhcp traffic.  8 min may be very good in some case, but I do not think it should be the default value.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-01-28 06:47:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Saying "there will be a lot of DHCP traffic" isn't a convincing argument. If some people would argue that the default should be days or weeks I would legitimately like to see them argue that. So far I haven't seen any reasons other than the general "reduce DHCP traffic" goal. If that's really the only goal, why do we stop at 24 hours when we could just set the lease to an infinite length?

Even though some other datacenters use 24 hours, it's not a valid comparison  because most other datacenters do not have a system like Neutron that strictly controls which IP addresses can be used. If a static lease changes in a normal datacenter, it doesn't instantly break traffic from the current lease holder, which is what happens with Neutron.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-01-28 06:57:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

To elaborate a bit... Brian, when you change the static lease for a client that uses the Linksys router to get a DHCP lease, is that client blocked from sending or receiving any traffic on the network until it moves to the new address?

The point isn't to compare the lease times in a vacuum, the problem is that Neutron completely blocks clients using an outdated address, which is traditionally not the case on datacenter networks.

For example, take a look at DHCP snooping. It offers similar IP spoofing protections as Neutron, however the switch does it based on observing DHCP messages from a trusted DHCP server. That means that an change to a DHCP lease on the DHCP server does not block the client's traffic (since it's sourced from an address that was issued by DHCP). Contrarily, when a Neutron port's IP is updated, the firewall rules are updated on the compute node immediately and the old IP is blocked."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-05-21 21:29:18.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

This review is > 4 weeks without comment, and failed Jenkins the last time it was checked. We are abandoning this for now. commit_message:
Decrease the default DHCP lease time to 8 minutes

This patch decreases the default DHCP lease time to 8 minutes.
This is to allow VMs to regain connectivity faster after their
IP address is changed. With the current default, a VM could remain
unreachable for up to 12 hours if no proactive action is taken
(e.g. restarting the VM, logging into the console, etc).

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1415221
Change-Id: If6d5e7d836a32e712937734af80c1f6313565118

commit_message:
Updated help message for router-update command

neutron help router-update was not displaying all the available
options (--name and --admin-state-up).

Updated the help message to display these as well.

Change-Id: I32583e5a87fae8a8332172c94adc364dc8188883
Closes-bug: #1406794

commit_message:
ipv6: simplify enable_ipv6_ra

* don't disable radvd in a function called enable_*;
* assume caller calls the function only if there are some ipv6 ports;
* explicitly disable radvd from _process_internal_ports() instead of relying on
  enable_ipv6_ra() to disable (sic!) unused radvd process for us.
* avoid redundant ip version checks in RA module.

Change-Id: I9cfbdc78b4f81270d5e811ef656876d0f6f59cb8

commit_message:
ML2 Type Driver refactor part 3

This commit builds on top of part 2 to introduce differentiation
between provider and tenant networks.

Change-Id: Ic77ade6b1d1be9af2f3503cc17e869f0e2493e26
Implements: Blueprint ml2-type-driver-refactor

To me, verifying that the sanity check doesn't blow up because of a change in one of the underlying libraries is sufficient functional testing. Maybe it is just a lack of imagination on my part, by I'm having trouble thinking of what a functional test for this sanity check would like."}, {'account_id': 10536, 'date': '2014-12-10 09:55:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

* all sanity checks out there implemented the same way. If you want to change the requirements of testing sanity checks, please discuss in weekly meeting and refactor them all in another ticket. Ping pong me here to add and remove does not help.

Tri Hoang Vo: Please submit a new patch without the unit test addition.  Save it in case Mark resurfaces and makes a compelling argument for a subsequent patch to add it back, but no sanity check to date has been required to add unit testing for the specific reason that the system interaction-heavy nature of the tests means they end up mock-heavy and mostly duplicate the logic in the sanity check.  I also do not see any reason for additional functional testing because, as you say, the result would be entirely host-dependent.

Mark: Sanity checks to-date have not required the same rigor as code that executes as part of a runtime production environment, hence the minimal testing requirement of 'can be invoked without error'.   The cost of maintaining unit tests and detailed functional testing for the checks was deemed unnecessarily high by those involved in their introduction.  Given that the checks are intended to be a shared resource for deployment tools to rely on, it is the responsibility of the maintainers of those tools to maintain the checks in the face of system-specific problems that they uncover."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-12-19 02:49:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

I recognize that the bar has been very low for validating sanity checks; however past behavior should not stop us from raising it.  Untested code bit rots and hoping that packagers tell us something is broken seems backwards.'}, {'account_id': 5756, 'date': '2014-12-19 04:18:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

mark: Also, it isn't just about the bar being low. I can't think of a way to write a functional test for this. It is a single function that should return either True or False and that return value is entirely dependent on the external system. A single system can't both pass and fail the test. So my question is, what type of functional test would we write here?"}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2014-12-19 15:48:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

Mark:  Given a limited amount of manpower to ensure the quality of the code, I think it's important to focus our efforts on testing that actually provides benefit, and I'm not the only one that believes that requiring test additions on non-critical sanity checks is not worth the effort.  Comprehensive functional testing is a non-starter due to the checks being entirely system-dependent in their execution, and the best that could be achieved would be unit tests that duplicated the logic of the code.  Under the circumstances, I don't think your -1 is valid and I would appreciate it if you would revisit."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2014-12-19 17:05:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-23 17:57:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified-1

check if it is safe to delete namespace when config dhcp or router
_delete_namespaces is True, to disable the config if is not safe to
delete

The check creates 2 test netns and tries to remove one namespace when
another one is mounted (i.e busy to sleep). If remove fails, clean up
the test by deleting the namespaces when they are not busy anymore

Integration tested with iproute version 20111117-1ubuntu2 for a
failed scenario and 20111117-1ubuntu2.3 for succeed

Change-Id: Idd8b1688477f72e420df5eab97a836a278f49dec

commit_message:
Detect if iproute2 allows delete namespace

sanity check if it is safe to delete namespace when config dhcp or
router_delete_namespaces is enabled. The check creates 2 test netns
and tries to remove one namespace when another one is mounted (i.e
busy to sleep). If remove fails, clean up the test by deleting the
namespaces when not sleep.

This check followed the steps 1,2,7,8 reported by Red Hat to reproduce
the issue https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1062685
For Ubuntu:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/iproute/+bug/1238981

Integration tested with iproute version 20111117-1ubuntu2 for a failed
scenario and 20111117-1ubuntu2.3 for succeed by calling:
neutron-sanity-check --delete_ip_namespace or
neutron-sanity-check --config-file /etc/neutron/l3_agent.ini or
neutron-sanity-check --config-file /etc/neutron/dhcp_agent.ini

Change-Id: Idd8b1688477f72e420df5eab97a836a278f49dec
Closes-Bug: 1253135

commit_message:
portbinding: introduce dev_group attribute

Add a 'binding:dev_group' attribute that allows to
specify device group for a port that would be
used in nova to define VF/PF placement.

Needed for bp:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/libvirt-sriov-nic-bonding

Change-Id: I1bfcc90c878ec04796372ad97542c40bec6b2391

commit_message:
get_vm_port_hostid should log PortNotFound Exception

When there are two or more Neutron Server deployed,
delete FloatingIP agent gateway port fails under
certain scenarios when a VM port associated with
floatingip gets deleted before the the floatingip
agent gateway port is deleted.

So when the second process comes in to delete the
floatingip agent gateway port, it calls the
get_vm_port_hostid with a fip['port_id'] that is
already been deleted and so PortNotFound exception
is raised when get_port is called.

This patch addresses the issue by checking for the
valid port_id before it calls the get_port in
get_vm_port_hostid and also logs a debug message
when PortNotFound Exception is raised.

Change-Id: Ie34e29d695a15d05de1fe75b7422f75adbb49152
Closes-Bug: #1408855

commit_message:
Untangle functional test_l3_agent test from unit tests

Move the following functions into a new l3_helpers module and reuse those
functions from both types of tests:

- get_ha_interface,
- prepare_router_data,
- router_append_interface.

Change-Id: Id2f694b6ea42d5c605ead89bf993c3e7c0eb9fc8

commit_message:
test_l3_agent: hide L3NATAgent arguments under a helper method

In next patches, I want to define HOSTNAME as a class attribute so that
it's possible to define it once in a parent class. So as a preparatory
step, move manual HOSTNAME argument passes to L3NATAgent under a
separate method to avoid additional burden on reviewers.

Change-Id: Iaff23ef378c0d163b681b54bd80229ea6374fe5b

commit_message:
Moved common code to mock L3 agent into a separate class

This code will be reused from all unit tests that want to instantiate
and process updates for mocked L3 agents.

Change-Id: I15354b83f4f85b71af37f223010a9c9f86811a4c

tests: moved unit tests for neutron.agent.linux.ra module

Those tests should be unbound from general L3 agent unit tests to make
it clear what's covered by tests (not many) and what's not (a lot).

commit_message:
pep8: validate neutron-rootwrap-xen-dom0

Move the code into .py file so that flake8 validates it.

This move requires some changes to pass pep8 checks. Specifically,
- some whitespacing and line wrapping rules to apply,
- adopt oslo.serialization.jsonutils instead of json.

Provide executable via console_scripts entry instead of
bin/neutron-rootwrap-xen-dom0.

Change-Id: Iac07098fbf09c560ca1b511858f768d3eb87352f

commit_message:
Return false for empty subnet_ids

check_ports_exist_on_l3agent checks if there exists one port whose
binding host is the same as the input l3 agent, and whose subnet is
attached to the input router. But if subnet_ids returned by
get_subnet_ids_on_router is empty, get_ports will return all the
ports since filter with empty 'subnet_id' is ignored in get_ports.
With empty subnet_ids, check_ports_exist_on_l3agent should just
return false instead.

Change-Id: I261fe26335e9bc94ec3a87c70bb3c2add32d01e4
Closes-Bug: #1417908

commit_message:
Restart l3 agent services leads to firewall error

when restart the vpn and l3 agent, the firewall rule apply to all tenants' router.
   step:
   1. Create network and router in A and B tenant.
   2. Create a firewall in A tenant.
   3. Restart vpn and l3 agent serivce.
   4. ip netns exec qrouter-B_router_uuid iptables -L -t filter -vn
Then I find the firewall rule in chain neutron-l3-agent-FORWARD and neutron-vpn-agen-FORWARD.

Closes-Bug: #1398267
Change-Id: If83044f3790b307e5fdbd91d90c598b30c8f4174

commit_message:
Eliminate defer_apply_on/off in iptables manager

Go all in with the context manager based implementation for deferring
application of iptables rules to discourage use of them which can lead to
assymmetrical usage.  For firewall, since _on/_off are in the interface, use
__enter__ and __exit__ methods explicitly.

Change-Id: I024e15a265c3e112a89ce91fe0f5564fb40528a2
Needed-By: I824b2f5d1b95549df7225e23dbcc718290ecd71d

'}, {'created': '2015-02-10 20:53:33.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent race conditions on DVR FIP resources

Multiple threads can step on each other while
adding or removing resources needed for DVR
floating IPs such as Agent gateway port and
FIP namespace. A conditional lock is added here
that comes into effect only for DVRs.

Change-Id: Ic7315aef7bcbc109f0c0e4d2696de357d08bbe3c
related-bug: #1415522
'}, {'created': '2015-02-10 21:23:55.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent race conditions on DVR FIP resources

Multiple threads can step on each other while
adding or removing resources needed for DVR
floating IPs such as Agent gateway port and
FIP namespace. A conditional lock is added here
that comes into effect only for DVRs.

commit_message:
Prevent race conditions on DVR FIP resources

Multiple threads can step on each other while
adding or removing resources needed for DVR
floating IPs such as Agent gateway port and
FIP namespace. A conditional lock is added here
that comes into effect only for DVRs.

Change-Id: Ic7315aef7bcbc109f0c0e4d2696de357d08bbe3c
related-bug: #1415522

commit_message:
PPTP VPN agent support

Currently, the service driver is shared with ipsec, but the device
driver is seperated. This is for making ipsec and ppp co-exist in
one depolyment. The accel-ppp driver now is fully supported for pptp.

NOTE: because of the pptpd deamon couldn't specify credential file,
so there is a problem to using this driver when associating or
disassociating credential from connection.

Implement blueprint: pptp-vpn-support
Change-Id: Ib14023854be8f6d00d9f39cda32aff69b454bf60

commit_message:
Fix dist_fip_count problem during router migration

When router is migrating from legacy to distributed,
ri object in l3 agent is a LegacyRouter object instead
of DvrRouter object. Therefore it doesn't have dist_fip_count
attribute. This patch fixed the AttributeError in this
scenario.

Change-Id: Iceeffb8d0bc6067db8ef23774d9b4a3b991245ee
Closes-Bug: 1421042

I think this is the correct direction to be heading into.'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2015-03-11 15:36:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

This is just something to think about and maybe discuss, not necessarily a recommendation to change the current approach: I've been wondering if it is sensible to create (but obviously not run) tasks from inside a transaction? If so, why not get rid of postcommit methods altogether, and have the precommit methods return a task if they need asynchronous work done? This would simplify the driver API and potentially streamline the code. But the main reason to consider it is that It might facilitate recovery from server crashes by allowing the tasks to be made persistent as part of the same transaction that modifies the resource's state."}, {'account_id': 8792, 'date': '2015-03-11 18:25:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Bob, yes that's the idea.  In the first round I wanted to maintain the APIs but give the idea what is expected.  In the long run, the post-commit phase doesn't make much sense in this approach.  It's only a set of tasks that are collected and run outside of transactions and outside of the REST context."}, {'account_id': 8792, 'date': '2015-03-11 22:18:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

This was discussed in ML2 meeting again today.  Two main points from there:

1) Allow changing of state from ACTIVE -> Creating based on some event.
2) Allow operations while in Intermediate state

About #1:
To be able to do that one would need to generate an event through the REST API.  Update the state (and trigger whatever is needed), e.g.  One cannot do it as part of ML2 -- the plugin shouldn't be involved in monitoring and corrective actions.  That should be outside the scope of this effort.  Something like that is useful but I don't think it will fly with the current neutron design.

About #2:
There are a few complications that we'll need to deal with when allowing operations while in intermediate state.  Some of them are mentioned below.
2.1) Make the Queue (of pending events) persistent
2.2) Processing events in the order they arrived could be very wasteful.  E.g. there could be a bunch of updates and then a delete request.  Should the delete really wait for the updates? How about update event X and then an update event Y which are independent and updating the same attribute (assuming the next update doesn't depend on the previous update)?  If updateX and updateY are waiting in the queue does it make sense to even execute updateX ?

If we really want to solve #2.2 we'll end up needing some sort of policy language and the building a scheduler :)

To avoid some of these complexities, I think we might be better off using the solution where we have a state machine and permit only certain events in a given state (e.g. a delete event could be permitted in all states except Deleting perhaps).

It will be good to discuss specific use cases here though.  Please log your thoughts here.

shivharis, please comment on specifics - I think you are interested in this."}, {'account_id': 8792, 'date': '2015-03-11 22:22:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Also, about the persistent queue we'll have to maintain could be problematic.  Now the user doesn't know what happened to the request except that it will be eventually done. When exactly isn't clear.  Plus we'll need to handle this probably at a higher level than the plugin as it deals with the API."}, {'account_id': 6558, 'date': '2015-03-18 06:23:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Manish, et. all, 

When I am thinking about this solution, I am thinking about two use cases: 
1) South bound transactions - In this case, we need to ensure that the transactions are sync'ed correctly with the back-ends. I think this proposal very nicely addresses this. 
2) Once in  stable state, the back-end can reset and loose the state. We need to rebuild the state in the back-end to bring it back into the state where the front-end (i.e neutron/ML2 DB) and the back-end are in sync (which is similar/same as 1)) While the state is in the process of being synced, if the front-end keep changing the state of the resources, achieving the sync will be never ending dilema. Therefore, it may be prudent to move the state of these resources in to intermediate state so that front-end do not change the state of these resources while they are being sync'ed. Therefore, we need to think through this. 

One thought is to allow the back-end (drivers) to move the state of these resources in to intermediate state. Alternatively, we can think about having a global state which could indicate "system error state". In ether case, we need to "freeze" the system state so that the system can be brought back into the operational state.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-05-21 21:28:39.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

This review is > 4 weeks without comment, and failed Jenkins the last time it was checked. We are abandoning this for now. Feel free to reactivate the review by pressing the restore button and leaving a 'recheck' comment to get fresh test results."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-05-21 21:28:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

This review is > 4 weeks without comment, and failed Jenkins the last time it was checked. We are abandoning this for now. Feel free to reactivate the review by pressing the restore button and leaving a 'recheck' comment to get fresh test results."}]

commit_message:
WIP: ml2 async proof-of-concept

This is based on earlier work (manishg, gus):
I35971770d87acb353333782150937ace5f4b9db5
Iaa52c6c11b32963735b0b16008fdeb6bb5b60e17

This is mainly doing the same as current ml2 with introduction
of taskflow.  In subsequent iterations, I'll slowly add intermediate
states and move out the engine out after REST response.

PatchSet 3:
* added documentation
* reorganized the code a little bit
* need to work on some unit tests
* will add async in next patch set
* added TODOs to indicate future patch set updates

Change-Id: Ibb75bb6295eca0496281e60202b95e9abf66cf8d

Unfortunately this is not the right way to fix this problem. Updating a row already locks it, the issue is that one agent will update the row first, then the other agent but using stale data. The problem is made worse since the dhcp agent is using port data that are cached, doesn't retrieve them directly from the db here [1] .

A possible fix would be to use a compare and swap strategy.

commit_message:
Add row lock when update dhcp reserved port

To avoid race condition when two dhcp agent using a reserved dhcp
port, put a row lock when update port for dhcp reserved port.

Change-Id: I3d319e9647960d8eb8e4b85ac9e2e56e2d762ea1
Closes-Bug: #1425402

commit_message:
WIP: Avoid assigned port as a second gateway to an existing router

The manually created port can be assign as a
--device_owner='network:router_gateway' to a router that already
have a default gateway which cause one router to have two default
gateways.

Partial-bug: #1430345

Change-Id: I01c901bc20f1a3e51b9a7d386f3c97e3925d1955

commit_message:
Change default sg table's name into plural

In general, we use plural words to represent table name.
This patch also fix some nits mentioned in review
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/142101

Change-Id: I047e22d987ec20954caab6857381810a44aca71e
Closes-Bug: 1416813

commit_message:
A cleanup of dhcp_agent_scheduler.py

This is a cleanup move the double coding into a separate method and
reuse from both schedule() and auto_schedule_networks().

Change-Id: I10cb5adb32a2fe18a301038f349b2e3504980abb

commit_message:
Add script to copy neutron tests

This change adds a script to automate the copying of neutron test
modules used by neutron-fwaas.

Usage:
  tools/copy_neutron_tests $NEUTRON_FOLDER

Change-Id: I61ec017035bd18ce6b5095fa87577f197952c75b

commit_message:
Remove qg from router namespace for DVR migration

Currently, when migrating a legacy router to distributed
router, associated floating IP no longer works because
qg device is still in qrouter namespace.

This is due to ovs-vsctl del qg port is execuated together
with add port operation. This fix separate the two ovs-vsctl
operations.

Change-Id: I82ea89f1695f1e6e7c7b8ab4e39ee969d7312a6d
Closes-Bug: 1405528

This change describes the overall proposed process and major work
items required.  More implementation details are still needed.

commit_message:
Apply Floating NAT only on the external interface

Specify the external interface in the Floating IP
iptables NAT rules. This fixes issue when using
Floating IP with extra routes.

Change-Id: Idda448c9eaeb43e83d6b0f4b5da0239ccad3cdbd
Closes-bug: #1375994

commit_message:
Split out get_sync_data from L3_NAT_dbonly_mixin

This patch splits out get_sync_data logic from L3_NAT_dbonly_mixin
and L3_NAT_with_dvr_db_mixin.
If wanted, the split logic would be a part of
(a subclass of) L3RpcCallback later.

Change-Id: Ib1ce939b0fb4ad81f67e2e2f552cbdcd4396ac83
Closes-Bug: #1177106

I'm missing how you determine the max packet size of an encapsulated packet.  Can you explain?

That aside, I take issue with one of your functions as it's badly named and undocumented.

On the positive side, I don't think garyk's -1 is valid.  He's got a couple of nits that look like personal taste and the rest of the points he makes would make the patch worse - as it stands it truly does check sanity, and the checks he proposes look like weaker versions to me.  That said, you could *also* check veth_mtu, but it's only applicable to certain plugging types and the conditions become somewhat complex."}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2015-01-21 21:26:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2015-01-21 21:42:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

(4 comments)

Thanks for the reviews guys.

Ian, I add the overhead each tunnel type adds and assume that the instances use the default MTU value of 1500. Then, assuming the instances do use this default MTU value, the br-tun interfaces will add an additional encap (size to be determined by configured tunnel types), resulting in the MTU that the physical interface should be set to. For example, if the chosen tunnel type is VXLAN (which adds 50 bytes), then packets leaving br-tun will contain a maximum size of 1500+50, resulting in a wanted MTU of 1550 in the physical interface.

Hopefully this answers your question. If it doesn't do let me know :)"}, {'account_id': 704, 'date': '2015-01-21 21:44:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-2

I strongly believe that Neutron should not take care of validating the MTU configuration. The solution here propose may potentially break production deployment that handles network interfaces configuration different. I have included more comments on the the bug description in launchpad.'}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2015-01-22 17:13:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Edgar, as Assaf mentioned on the launchpad bug, this change doesn't break anything. it merely adds a warning to the sanity script warning if the MTU configuration might be incorrect. The spec which intends to solve the MTU issue was approved and can be found here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/105989/

Can you clarify what part of my patch you're concerned about?"}, {'account_id': 704, 'date': '2015-01-27 14:25:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

John, I was not aware of that plugin. You can imagine that we have N number of BPs and it is almost impossible to cover all of them. I read this mtu-selection-and-advertisement spec carefully and now I see how this commit is related to it.
Please, include the spec in your commit message and then it will be easier for reviewers to find out the justification of your commit. I remove my -2 but is still -1 until you address Gary's comments and update your commit message.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-21 09:11:24.000000000', 'message': "Add sanity check for wrong MTU when using tunnels

When setting up a multi-node setup which uses tunnels, packets from one
node to the other is encapsulated in tunnels (VXLAN, GRE and STT are the
current options offered), which causes the packets to increase in size.
In other words, when using GRE, a packet of size 1500 will be changed
and the GRE header (24 bytes) will be added, causing the actual sent
packet to be 1524 bytes.

In case the underlying infrastructure's MTU is set to 1500, the packets
will drop somewhere along the way, causing problems which can be
somewhat difficult to debug.

This patch adds a sanity check for whether or not the physical
interface's MTU is high enough (for our previous example, 1524 is
needed), and if not a warning is printed. This is only a warning since
there could be other solutions (for example, the instance's MTU can be
lowered to a suitable size manually, fixing the problem).

Closes-bug: #1375815
Change-Id: I12d54159da3fed5223ae97dd01ef0b6948c2915d

commit_message:
Add sanity check for wrong MTU when using tunnels

When setting up a multi-node setup which uses tunnels, packets from one
node to the other is encapsulated in tunnels (VXLAN and GRE are the
current options offered), which causes the packets to increase in size.
In other words, when using GRE, a packet of size 1500 will be changed
and the GRE header (42 bytes) will be added, causing the actual sent
packet to be 1542 bytes.

In case the underlying infrastructure's MTU is set to 1500, there may be
a performance degradation due to the potential fragmentation of frames,
causing problems which can be somewhat difficult to debug.

This patch adds a sanity check for whether or not the physical
interface's MTU is high enough (for our previous example, 1524 is
needed), and if not a warning is printed. This is only a warning since
there could be other solutions (for example, the instance's MTU can be
lowered to a suitable size manually, fixing the problem).

Closes-bug: #1375815
Change-Id: I12d54159da3fed5223ae97dd01ef0b6948c2915d

commit_message:
Fix neutron.tests.tempest.config use of cfg.CONF

Tempest configuration previously used the oslo_config global cfg.CONF,
which conflicted with Neutron's use of the same global.  This change
moves tempest config to use a local ConfigOpts instance instead of the
global to eliminate the potential for conflict.

Change-Id: Ibcf0a08a624a08ceb3da4c3f4df021bbed9bf453

commit_message:
Forbid update router port to have more than one ip

A port with more than one ips is not allowed to be attached to a
router, so we should also forbid updating a router port to have
more then one ips.

Change-Id: I956dcb2a1a0d927cb4331df91a8bfeac0694e9fe
Closes-Bug: #1410688

Test attaching router to IPv6 subnets

1. Test attaching router interface to SLAAC networks when
its IP is set explicitly during subnet setup.
2. Same as p. 1 but for IP is set by default during subnet setup.

commit_message:
InvalidQuotaValue should use error code 403

The neutron InvalidQuotaValue exception extends
Conflict (HttpConflict, Error code 409)  but
that doesn't really make sense for this exception.
It should be rather 403 (Forbidden).

So updated the code to raise 403 instead of 409
and added a test case for the same.

Change-Id: Iec2da682ab645b90d5d3fc548c3ca4b15d62c011
Closes-Bug: #1405099

Currently server joins SecurityGroupPortBinding and SecurityGroupRule
table to retrieve security group rules of a port, so an empty security
group is not returned. This will cause trouble if enhanced RPC is
enabled. The security_groups field in the RPC response will not
contain the id of the empty security group so agent will not update

commit_message:
Use left join for security group retrieve

Currently server joins SecurityGroupPortBinding and SecurityGroupRule
table to retrieve security group rules of a port, so an empty security
group is not returned. This will cause trouble if enhanced RPC is
enabled. The security_groups field in the RPC response will not
contain the id of the empty security group so agent will not update
this security group. Thus it will not take effect deleting the last
rule in a security group.

This patch left joins SecurityGroupPortBinding and SecurityGroupRule
table to ensure that empty security group can also be returned.

Change-Id: I9713a607a85d4bdcb9730d00cf8551d142acfb0f
Closes-Bug: #1420056

[{'created': '2015-03-03 10:01:48.000000000', 'message': 'Move pylint checks to pep8 testenv

The tox.ini file has been updated such that the pylint violation checks
have been moved to the pep8 testenv. If pylint is executed as a separate
job, handling potential unexpected breakages would become a difficult job
because we need to get infra involved. Also, an extra node needs to be
spinned, when the checks can easily be handled by the node for the pep8
job.

Further, having pylint running with tox -epep8 would help developers
become aware of pylint violations sooner rather than later, if they forget
to run the pylint testenv too before submitting the change.

Change-Id: I9c2d6016cef81448099db07df11c7534cdb1af34
'}]
commit_message:
Move pylint checks to pep8 testenv

The tox.ini file has been updated such that the pylint violation checks
have been moved to the pep8 testenv. If pylint is executed as a separate
job, handling potential unexpected breakages would become a difficult job
because we need to get infra involved. Also, an extra node needs to be
spinned, when the checks can easily be handled by the node for the pep8
job.

Further, having pylint running with tox -epep8 would help developers
become aware of pylint violations sooner rather than later, if they forget
to run the pylint testenv too before submitting the change.

Change-Id: I9c2d6016cef81448099db07df11c7534cdb1af34

commit_message:
Update neutronclient shell to use shared arguments from Session

The neutronclient implemented it's own version of the CLI arguments that
are now provided by keystoneclient's session object. This changeset
converts neutron over to utilizing the shared argument registration.

Change-Id: Icb0ce23f04177b935f36b71c2e54ea34087fd7bb
Closes-Bug: 1434105

commit_message:
l2population_rpc: Refactor RPC endpoint

- Separate the endpoint class from the mixin in order to make it clear
  which methods are intended to be exposed via RPC.  This also makes the
  RPC versioning easier to maintain.

- Adapt ofagent and OVS agent.

Partial-Bug: #1413041
Partial-Bug: #1112634
Change-Id: I1b043b36c313ee8e543973bbeb992b319a003bbe

Hi sajuptpm,

I am not yet old neutron developer, so probably my comment is not totally correct,
so you are warned:)

- Related blueprint does not describe what is the expected fuctionality:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/opencontrail-ipam-extension
So it is not clear for me what this patch is expected to do,
so probably I make wrong assumptions about it.

- Is this patch related to other IPAM work, which is in progress for Kilo?
I mean these patches:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/134339/ IPAM Interface
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/147479/ IPAM Driver Loader
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/150485/ Reference IPAM Driver
If yes, I would expect that your IPAM implementation would implement IPAM Interface.
Interface is still changing.

- The idea of CRUD for IPAM is not very clear for me, it does not fit my understanding of what IPAM is.
IPAM is IP address management, in context of my work it is interface that allows to allocate(manage) subnets and ip addresses.
This interface allows to use 3rd party solutions for managing ip address space.
So I consider single IPAM as instance of IPAM Driver.
Does it match your understanding of what IPAM is?

I am pretty sure that describing exected behavior in blueprint/spec will help a lot to answer my questions.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2015-02-04 20:15:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

to put Pavel's comments in another perspective, it would have been more logic if the Open Contrail plugin would have leveraged and contributed to the effort the rest of the community is making towards configurable IPAM.

That's said, this is not possible for the architecture of the plugin itself, which cannot integrate with anything else in neutron due to its nature. We've already been over this argument.

Anyway, what concerns me here is how this patch plays with core-plugin-decomposition, as there is pretty much a freeze on plugin specific extensions.

If you feel you need an exception, please go to the mailing list."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-12 05:37:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

Do you intend to continue to work on this patch or is that no longer needed after the code split? If it's not needed, please abandon the patch or mark as work in progress so it doesn't sit in the queue of patches requiring review.

Other than that, this probably needs an APIImpact tag in the commit message since it's adding an extension, but everything else looks okay. I can't offer much extra insight for a change that just passes everything directly through."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-05-21 21:27:49.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
OpenContrail IPAM Extension

Following IPAM delegates are implemented
Create IPAM
Get IPAM/IPAMs
Update IPAM
Delete IPAM

Change-Id: I3662967c3ae4957c1013fbcc376f5f8c7ac383b9
Implements: blueprint opencontrail-ipam-extension

commit_message:
Fixes sync between Arista ML2 driver and EOS

A bug in the sync code prevented the Arista ML2 driver from syncing with EOS.
This patch fixes the bug and adds some unit tests to ensure that the sync
behaves as expected.

DocImpact: The default sync_interval has been changed from 180 to 20 seconds.

Closes-Bug: 1411383
Change-Id: I42b937874b866e975f159e0becec7bf7f99075ac

commit_message:
Check if the port is ACTIVE before sending update_fdb message

When a port is not ACTIVE, l2pop don't have to notify any change
of its IPs, since no agent should have the fdb entrie for a port
which is not ACTIVE.

This patch also fixes a nit introduced by
I1864c0882cda7eddc9ced519ed3f96c91b2b63f3
which is raising a misspelled exception

Change-Id: I269de325950dac998bf02704a174bbb15ef2b6ac
Closes-bug: #1414650

Yes, and we are going to achieve this feature by the following steps:

For each physical bridge,
(1) Move all the flows in table_0 to table_x
(2) Add arp responder flows in table_y
(3) Add flows in table_0, for arp packets, resubmit to table_y, others resubmit to table_x
(4) If arp packets don't match any flows in table_y, resubmit to table_x"}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-04-12 05:37:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
OVS agent supports arp responder for VLAN

This commit[1] introduces a new agent configuration "l2pop_network_types".
In ofagent, this configuration is used to enable arp responder for non-tunnel
network types like VLAN, using the l2pop information. This patch adds an
option to switch this feature in OVS agent.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/112947

Change-Id: Ideb2bd9f9c230a2a497080c9ff57a4c6f59ec375
Closes-Bug: #1413056

[{'created': '2015-03-11 10:19:02.000000000', 'message': "Make L2 DVR Agent start successfully without an active neutron server

If the L2 Agent is started before the neutron controller
is available, it will fail to obtain its unique DVR MAC
address, and fall-back to operate in non-DVR mode
permanently.

This fix does two things:
1. Makes the L2 Agent attempt to retry obtaining a DVR MAC
address up to five times on initialization, which should be
enough time for RPC to be successful.  On failure, it will
fall back to non-DVR mode, ensuring that basic switching
continues to be functional.

2. Correctly obtains the current operating mode of the
L2 Agent in _report_state(), instead of only reporting
the configured state.  This operating mode is carried
in 'in_distributed_mode' attribute of agent state, and
is separate from the existing enable_distributed_routing
static config that is already sent.

Closes-bug: #1364215
(cherry picked from commit 51303b5fe4785d0cda76f095c95eb4d746d7d783)

commit_message:
Make L2 DVR Agent start successfully without an active neutron server

If the L2 Agent is started before the neutron controller
is available, it will fail to obtain its unique DVR MAC
address, and fall-back to operate in non-DVR mode
permanently.

This fix does two things:
1. Makes the L2 Agent attempt to retry obtaining a DVR MAC
address up to five times on initialization, which should be
enough time for RPC to be successful.  On failure, it will
fall back to non-DVR mode, ensuring that basic switching
continues to be functional.

2. Correctly obtains the current operating mode of the
L2 Agent in _report_state(), instead of only reporting
the configured state.  This operating mode is carried
in 'in_distributed_mode' attribute of agent state, and
is separate from the existing enable_distributed_routing
static config that is already sent.

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/openvswitch/agent/ovs_neutron_agent.py

Change-Id: I5fd9bf4163eafa321c5fca7ffb7901ae289f323b
Closes-bug: #1364215
(cherry picked from commit 51303b5fe4785d0cda76f095c95eb4d746d7d783)

[{'created': '2015-04-14 13:19:36.000000000', 'message': "Add events on dropped packet by security groups firewall.

This patch includes:
 - A boolean event parameter addition to the security group entity
(API/DB/Propagation to the Firewall driver).
 - An extension of the existing iptables firewall driver that sends
events to ceilometer

To use these patch with complete events you need:
 - To activate ceilometer to your devstack configuration file adding
these lines (section [[local|localrc]]):

enable_service ceilometer-acompute ceilometer-acentral
ceilometer-anotification ceilometer-collector
enable_service ceilometer-alarm-evaluator,ceilometer-alarm-notifier
enable_service ceilometer-api

 - To add parameter to 'ml2_conf.ini' file in your devstack
configuration file adding these lines:

[securitygroup]
firewall_event_driver=neutron.agent.linux.iptables_firewall_event_syslog.IptablesFirewallSyslogEventDriver

 - Add the new events definition at the end of the 'file
event_definitions.yaml' in ceilometer conf folder:

- event_type: security.groups.firewall.drop.*
  traits: &security_groups_firewall
    src_ip:
      fields: payload.src_ip
    dst_port_number:
      fields: payload.dst_port_number
    protocol:
      fields: payload.protocol
    dst_ip:
      fields: payload.dst_ip
    dst_port_id:
      fields: payload.dst_port_id
    rule_type:
      fields: payload.rule_type
    time_stamp:
      fields: payload.time_stamp
    tenant_id:
      fields: payload.tenant_id

 - Associate an instance to a security group that have the event column
set to 1/true to receive the events.

Change-Id: I4defd2642cd70f3c2ee12f106c939a79d440c569
Status: Beta implementation for POC purpose
Implements: blueprint security-groups-dropped-packets-event
"}]
commit_message:
Add events on dropped packet by security groups firewall.

This patch includes:
 - A boolean event parameter addition to the security group entity
(API/DB/Propagation to the Firewall driver).
 - An extension of the existing iptables firewall driver that sends
events to ceilometer

To use these patch with complete events you need:
 - To activate ceilometer to your devstack configuration file adding
these lines (section [[local|localrc]]):

enable_service ceilometer-acompute ceilometer-acentral
ceilometer-anotification ceilometer-collector
enable_service ceilometer-alarm-evaluator,ceilometer-alarm-notifier
enable_service ceilometer-api

 - To add parameter to 'ml2_conf.ini' file in your devstack
configuration file adding these lines:

[securitygroup]
firewall_event_driver=neutron.agent.linux.iptables_firewall_event_syslog.IptablesFirewallSyslogEventDriver

 - Add the new events definition at the end of the 'file
event_definitions.yaml' in ceilometer conf folder:

- event_type: security.groups.firewall.drop.*
  traits: &security_groups_firewall
    src_ip:
      fields: payload.src_ip
    dst_port_number:
      fields: payload.dst_port_number
    protocol:
      fields: payload.protocol
    dst_ip:
      fields: payload.dst_ip
    dst_port_id:
      fields: payload.dst_port_id
    rule_type:
      fields: payload.rule_type
    time_stamp:
      fields: payload.time_stamp
    tenant_id:
      fields: payload.tenant_id

 - Associate an instance to a security group that have the event column
set to 1/true to receive the events.

Change-Id: I4defd2642cd70f3c2ee12f106c939a79d440c569
Status: Beta implementation for POC purpose
Implements: blueprint security-groups-dropped-packets-event

commit_message:
WIP Alternate Refactoring for Pluggable IPAM

This provides an alternate approach to the refactoring needed
for pluggable IPAM. In [1], the proposed approach does not require
changes to any plugins, only to the base class. The approach in
this patch requires changes to the plugin subclasses in order to
utilize pluggable IPAM; unchanged plugins will continue to use
the builtin IPAM.

The advantage of this patch is that the IPAM driver calls are
done prior to the start of the management layer's transaction.
This means that there is no open transaction during any external
API calls.

This is very much a WIP, it is only intended to demonstrate the
alternate approach. Some notes:
   * Only the create_port method is refactored
   * Much of the validation (such as _test_fixed_ips_for_port) is
     deferred to the driver layer.
   * There is no error handling
   * I haven't even looked to see if it will handle IPv6, auto-
     addressed ports, or router ports.
   * I borrowed the ipam/__init__.py changes from [1].
   * It is only very lightly tested: allocations for fixed IPs
     via the neutron CLI are working in the single-subnet case,
     as well as allocations when only a network ID is specified.
   * Since none of the subnet calls are refactored, you have to
     manual setup the database entries for them for the driver
     to know what to do.
   * IPAllocations are still stored, as that is the foreign key
     relationships defined by the Port object for its IPs.
   * The new driver is used for the actual allocations. This is
     done prior to the start of the transaction in the ML2
     create_port call.
   * Obviously the final routines would appear in the DB plugin
     not the ML2 plugin so they can be used by other plugins.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/153236

Change-Id: Id171afb3e9bafacd8b77ace9087f6ee2317c4054

OpenContrail plugin code split

- Removes main codes and unit tests of opencontrail plugin

Related to blueprint core-vendor-decomposition
Closes-bug: #1433397

commit_message:
Fix DVR SNAT unscheduling if host doesn't have service ports

The SNAT portion of a distributed router is scheduled when
the router is attached to an external network. It is deleted
when an internal interface is removed and there do not remain
any VMs, LB or DHCP ports on the subnet of the deleted interface.

When a DVR router interface is removed, the SNAT portion of the
router was unscheduled because the dvr_snat node was not hosting
VM, LB or DHCP ports. However, in this case, if the router still
has SNAT ports in other subnets, it was still unscheduled when
it should not have been.

This patch changes the unscheduling of the SNAT portion of a
distributed router so that it is unscheduled only when the external
interface of a router is deleted, which mirrors the logic of
SNAT scheduling.

Change-Id: Iffbcf10842ae861be05c43f4a68ce48fc016731b
Closes-Bug: #1443596

commit_message:
Handle 'ipset exists' errors when creating ipsets

When the parameters for an ipset are different from an existing
ipset with the same name, 'ipset create' will fail with an error
indicating that a set with the same name already exists even when
the '-exists' flag is present. This causes the agent to constantly
throw exceptions and stops it from configuring the security groupsi
correctly.

This was introduced by Ic0b5b38a840e737dc6be938230f4052974c8620f
where the default element limit was increased and it was made
configurable. Without this patch, the only work-around is to
manually destroy all of the IP sets before starting the agent
after changing the max elements.

This patch just catches the failure and checks for the 'exists'
string. If it finds it, it explicitly destroys the existing set
and any associated iptables rules (required to remove the set).
It then creates the new set with the different parameters.

Change-Id: I59e2e1c090cb95ee1bd14dbb53b6ff2c5e2713fd
Closes-Bug: #1444201

commit_message:
Stop openvswitch agent rpc connection on Exception

If exceptions are raised during neutron-server
initiation, this will result in lots
of fanout queues leak in RabbitMQ

There are many possible cases that will raise
exception
between self.setup_rpc() and consume_in_thread()
so this patch
catches and logs/stops connections.

Change-Id: I8ad0464e76462bbce13d044c5195225d261c25ba
Closes-Bug: #1434378

commit_message:
TLS capability extension implementation for lbaas v2

This change is part of LBaaS TLS capability feature
added to the neutron-lbaas advanced service repository
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/145085

The change is adding TLS related resources to the existing
LBaaS v2 extension resources

Change-Id: I0a67acf2bf0542bc1c34c2df64e58623ca16af06
Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-ssl-termination

commit_message:
Create the second vip return incorrect error code

Create the second vip use the same pool id,it returns 500 error.
It should return 409 error code.This will fix it.

Change-Id: I9b1c9647eeb158c69ebe47a64ff4fe684b7c01b0
Closes-Bug: bug #1402908

1.Create the first member by using address, protocol-port and one pool id.(successfully)
2.Create the second member by using the same address, protocol-port and one pool id.(failure)
And return "Internal Server Error (HTTP 500)"
The change will change it to 409 error.

Change-Id: I9c901a0b5c9d5fabd44dab7cbd15209f4bcb20ff
Closes-Bug: #1405091

commit_message:
Create the same member twice should not return 500 error

The change will change it to 409 error.

Change-Id: I9c901a0b5c9d5fabd44dab7cbd15209f4bcb20ff
Closes-Bug: #1405091

commit_message:
Updated type parameter in loadbalancer

Initially,  V2 API specification load balancer
healthmonitor has a parameter "type" which can
not be parsed by JSON parser because JSON also
also has type parameter

Now, it replaced by "healthmonitor_type"

Change-Id: I6071163bda76a2eb0619c7f7d597979f00febdbe
Closes-Bug: #1415336

commit_message:
Add service group as a firewall customized service

This patch introduces the model and extension framework
for implementing service group.
Two resources service_group and service_object are added,
modules can refer multiple service groups to allow the
user flexibilty to define their own groups and use them without impacting
the other users.
Each service object can be defined with a timeout value that can be used
to overwrite default session idle timeout value.
More info can be found at service group wiki
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/FWaaS/FWaaS-ServiceGroup
Implements: blueprint fwaas-customized-service for customized service
Authored-by: badveli vishnuvardhan <badveli_vishnuus@yahoo.com>
Change-Id: Iffb08f042d9198754ff6d30e5be0c74c3e141797

commit_message:
Fix vip_session_persistence's cookie_name always NULL

When update loadblance vip session-persistence cookie_name,
use args like:
--session-persistence type=dict \
type="SOURCE_IP", [cookie_name="test"]
The dict key is [cookie_name, not cookie_name, the same as the value.

To fix it, strip the bracket.

Change-Id: I2570b6eb0d3fb90ac6b11ffdf20d66639058abbd
Closes-Bug:#1405135

Many deployments pass /etc/neutron/neutron.conf as one of the config files to all of the agents and it frequently contains the DB connection string. So if someone is running the metadata agent on the same node as the neutron server, they are going to get warnings that they can't do anything about without moving their configuration options around.

This isn't really an actionable warning and logging it implies that it's something that should be looked into, which it shouldn't. The entire point of overriding the connection string is to make the agent ignore the database settings."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-31 09:04:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Add a warning log to remind user the metadata does not need DB connection,
so reset it.

L7 capability extension implementation for lbaas v2

This change is part of LBaaS L7 capability feature

LBaaS v2 extension resources

This is WIP

Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-l7-rules

Can you please clarify how neutron project is related to time sync?'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-04-04 20:42:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

See my comments in v2. It probably should hook into the neutron metadata proxy, and or the neutron router subsystem. So it would be related to neutron in that case.'}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-04-06 09:49:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Kevin:
1. 'Secondary' time source is an optional flexibility provided to the user for ensuring fail over cases of external NTP time servers. Coming to your idea about doing the synchronization via a common source (169.254.169.254) looks fine but in this case also we need to run separate NTP agents per tenant's namespace. These NTP agent in turn can have a secondary external time server for themselves and the VM's will just have to synchronize to a single source (169.254.169.254) running NTP functionality.
2. My intention is run separate NTP agents per namespace which will be similar to dnsmasq. Let's say your plugin router supports NTP then in this case NTP agents will not run and we just add some iptable rules to handle incoming NTP requests from different tenants.
3. Auth is an optional parameter. This could be valid if multiple tenants want to synchronize their timing from a single open source. If the tenants are sure about the authenticity then it can be avoided.
4. I agree with your idea about bonding the VM's to 169.254.169.254 for time synchronization. Will work upon this.How about running NTP in broadcast mode?"}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-04-06 09:50:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@enikanorov: 
This could be argued. We can either put this functionality in Nova (Compute) or Neutron. 
I have chosen neutron for the following reasons:

1. Neutron's advanced service framework is generic and can easily provide vendor's specific plugin support.

2. Neutron already support dnsmasq per namespace. I felt using the same concept for time synchronization could be easier.

3. Since NTP does it's functionality via a client-server approach which requires more networking stuff. 
So, I felt it could be a part of neutron."}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-04-06 09:52:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

@Kevin: Please check my comments inline.'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-04-06 16:01:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-04-07 09:43:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Hi Kevin, 

Thanks for your valuable comments. 
Please check the comments inline.

Vikram'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-04-07 14:03:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-04-08 02:16:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-04-08 15:56:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9237, 'date': '2015-04-08 16:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I just had a chat with some of the developers and they said that rather then setup a whole infrastructure for this, why not set ntp to use dhcp option 42.

The good news is the option can be set on most clouds today and the vm would get it. Either by /etc/neutron/dnsmasq-neutron.conf or using extra_dhcp_opts on a per port basis.

The bad news is, to enable all of the functionality we have in our blueprint, it needs to be set on a per subnet basis which is not implemented yet. See this blueprint:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/dhcp-options-per-subnet

I think we can probably abandon this blueprint in favor of this approach and getting dhcp-options-per-subnet implemented.

It also would probably be good to update the admin guide to make this solution apparent.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-04-09 21:37:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2

I see no reason this should be a part of Neutron. This could be built outside of Neutron.'}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-04-10 03:46:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Kyle,

Could you please suggest how to take up this idea forward. I feel the idea will help the cloud administrator and enhance existing time sync capability of Openstack.

Thanks
Vikram'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-04-11 03:08:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I'd suggest starting this in stackforge.  If you look at designate or trove, they are not in neutron proper (and are network agnostic, as this seems to be)."}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-04-11 03:22:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks for the suggestion Doug. How the code contributed in stackforge will help neutron? Whether such contribution is considered as a contribution towards openstack?'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-04-11 03:31:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

It depends on how you're defining a contribution to openstack. It's certainly a valuable place to start incubating code and gaining users, and once the idea gets further along, then it can be evaluated for inclusion in an existing project, or even becoming its own openstack project. commit_message:
Add capability of specifying Barbican version to client

While specifying the version of the Barbican API was possible before,
this was being ignored on the client and the default version was always
hardcoded. This CR now takes that into account and will append the
version to the base endpoint.

Change-Id: I2bd8bf64792dd91d7b79709398840c0c2d07a69d

(2 comments)

vagrant-swift-all-in-one is starting to get tooled up for go:

https://github.com/swiftstack/vagrant-swift-all-in-one/tree/hummingbird

^ more to come, I did the go install by hand.  I would love some input about your workflows tho - I feel like an autoremake watcher script (cribbed off autodoc) might happen.

Took me a minute to understand what this change did, finally got it nailed with with a curl upload directly to the object server, before object-server would 422 if etag had caps - now it will still 201, just like swift.obj.server

however near as I can tell if you use the same etag you just sent with PUT in an if-match header on a HEAD - you'll still get 412

Food for thought, maybe it would just be better if the proxy sanitized that header instead of leaking all the warts from the client facing API down to the object-server implementation?  You can still commit to swift.proxy.server on this branch yeah?

Also, we need to ask notmyname to like document how to merge master to feature branches - he's told me how at least once, but I can't ever remember."}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2015-05-15 14:26:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Remove instances of _base_url

The variable _base_url was not really necessary since we are setting up
the endpoint_override variable which will eventually be used when making
a request through the keystoneclient's session.

This is a step in getting the client to use the keystoneclient's
API more wisely. A subsequent CR will remove the need for the
endpoint_override and make use of keystoneclient's endpoint_filters to
discover the Barbican endpoint.

Change-Id: Id589c76fb5fe481a3dd48ee1baa26f7d19d2d1a1

Add id_attribute to base proxy calls

If the id attribute was not id, the base proxy was broken.

Closes-Bug: #1457513

commit_message:
Code clean up db.instance_get_all_by_host()

Replaces db.instance_get_all_by_host()
with objects.InstanceList.get_by_host()
also, fixed several unit test cases fail by using
mock to replace stub.

Closes-Bug: #1390483

Change-Id: I7da701f37d162f97b924cb8eede76de4f1c8bf7a

commit_message:
Initial element tests

Adding a test function which allows us to use elements to perform
element-specific tests. In order for this to work sanely, also adding
some configuration to our break system so we can assert on negative
tests.

Also adding a test for apt-sources to verify this code actually works.

Change-Id: I378a74255010eca192f5766b653f8a42404be5ea

commit_message:
Fixing broken Heat tests for Swift resources

I have encountered it recently. I just ran Heat tests for Swift
resources and saw that these tests are broken. It looks like no dsvm
check job runs these tests and that is why we didn't encounter this
issue earlier. I have found the commit that breaks these tests.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153681/

In order to fix the tests we should add the following code lines
to the file tempest/api/orchestration/stacks/test_swift_resources.py:

    @classmethod
    def setup_credentials(cls):
        super(SwiftResourcesTestJSON, cls).setup_credentials()
        stack_owner_role = CONF.orchestration.stack_owner_role
        operator_role = CONF.object_storage.operator_role
        cls.os = cls.get_client_manager(
            roles=[stack_owner_role, operator_role])

After adding these code lines we have working tests again.

Closes-Bug: #1455775

Change-Id: I5884149fef95c50d62ffde6e5c9488da1a9d6a55

commit_message:
Implement validation on the Identity V3 API

Use JSONSchema to validate CRUD operations on the V3 Identity resources.
This includes wrapping the create and update methods for Users and
Groups.

Co-Authored-By: Lin Hua Cheng <os.lcheng@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ia260838c85f897c52740217d8d222bb86edc11c6
bp: identity-api-validation
Closes-Bug: #999084

commit_message:
[Validation] Allow `required_clients' validate admin clients

Sometimes we need to validate if some clients are available
for admin endpoint.

So this patch adds optional `admin' key argument to validator
validation.required_clients for this purpose.

Change-Id: Ie393f3b0481c178a3442ac695ebba083ee1cbefd

[{'created': '2015-05-21 16:26:25.000000000', 'message': "Add test caller to scenario manager ssh connection failure for tracking

test_volume_boot_pattern (v1 and v2) has been failing with generic
SSHTimeout for awhile now but due to the very generic nature of the
failure we don't have a fingerprint in elastic-recheck for tracking the
problem.

This adds the specific error to the message that's logged and adds the
test caller so we can track specific tests hitting this failure rather
than everything that could possibly hit it and muddle the bug
categorization in elastic-recheck.

Related-Bug: #1355573

Change-Id: I7b37af339aea1be0cbe4bae1156e9f5dc20d0dd7
"}]
commit_message:
Add test caller to scenario manager ssh connection failure for tracking

test_volume_boot_pattern (v1 and v2) has been failing with generic
SSHTimeout for awhile now but due to the very generic nature of the
failure we don't have a fingerprint in elastic-recheck for tracking the
problem.

This adds the specific error to the message that's logged and adds the
test caller so we can track specific tests hitting this failure rather
than everything that could possibly hit it and muddle the bug
categorization in elastic-recheck.

Related-Bug: #1355573

Change-Id: I7b37af339aea1be0cbe4bae1156e9f5dc20d0dd7

commit_message:
Deprecate WritableLogger - used for eventlet logging

WritableLogger was used for example in Nova as a bridge to the
eventlet's logging mechanism. Eventlet has been enhanced in
0.17.2 to use python loggers directly, so we don't need this
anymore.

Closes-Bug: #1440773
Change-Id: I505a6e4946db88db4a1e57ed37f43bd203c7ab1f

commit_message:
[Context] Users cleanup should not fail without networking

Users context cleanup tries to remove default secgroup,
even if there is networking component not available.
This causes error on clouds with reduced components set (for example,
Fuel master node).

This patch disables default security group removal for these
specific cases.

Change-Id: I92987c11f2c7b0cb7bab0d0d9e052b30ffa95366
Closes-Bug: 1455474

commit_message:
Rename rally.cmd to rally.cli

There is module 'cmd' in standard library, and unittest's discover
does modify sys.path when running tests. This cause errors when running
unit tests in some environments (E.g. pycharm)

Change-Id: I4fd2d271da1b7fd300fbbeb6107aa958e716fd2b
Closes-Bug: 1457162

commit_message:
Revert "Loosen validation on matching trusted dashboard"

Loosening the validation introduce a security hole for unvalidated redirect.

For example: redirect_url=http://dashboard/sso?next=http://hacksite

This reverts commit fb6920e5fe1fef2fa32afe602d2bf93f18d48a3f.

Change-Id: I7e85b2b879f4c66c3664e8610d3ddbb999a5ac75
Closes-Bug: #1440958

commit_message:
Match order of iptables arguments to iptables-save

The way we were forming our iptables rules was not matching
the output of iptables-save. This caused the logic that preserves
counters to miss many of the rules.

This patch corrects the order for the comments and the allowed address
pairs to match the output order of iptables-save.

Closes-Bug: #1456823
Change-Id: I34c2249d0865485578767865c82414e1d813d563

enddate, the duration can't be calculated which leads to a:

ValueError: could not convert string to float

Check now if the duration is an empty string and add basic test

"}]
commit_message:
Fix ValueError in subunit_trace

When a subunit stream for a testcase doesn't contain start end
enddate, the duration can't be calculated which leads to a:

ValueError: could not convert string to float

Check now if the duration is an empty string and add basic test
coverage based on ddt for the subunit_trace command.

Change-Id: I9953019794ba53fcfcb20e32fecbe94da22c9565

commit_message:
Python 3: use six.string_types instead of basestring

In Python 3, there is no "basestring". In Python 3, "six.string_types" is
"basestring", and "str" in Python 3.

Change-Id: Ic22e932cbf3c4b75cd424f4b41428da869f197cf
Blueprint: neutron-python3
